{"title_page": "Philippine Scouts", "text_new": "{{about|the military unit|the youth movement|Boy Scouts of the Philippines}}\n{{More footnotes|date=May 2008}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=Philippine Scouts\n|image=[[File:12th Infantry Division SSI.svg|225px]]\n|caption=Philippine Scouts [[shoulder sleeve insignia]] from 1921\u20131947 was the head of the [[carabao]] ([[water buffalo]]) which symbolized the Philippines. The colors red and gold represented the islands' Spanish colonial roots.\n|dates=1901\u20131948\n|country={{flag|United States|1912}}<br>{{flag|Philippines|1936}}\n|allegiance={{flag|United States of America|1912}}<br>{{small|(1901\u20131946)}}\n* {{flagdeco|Philippines|1919}} [[Insular Government (Philippines)|Insular Government]]<br>{{small|(1901\u20131935)}}\n* {{flag|Commonwealth of the Philippines}}<br>{{small|(1935\u20131946)}}\n{{flag|Republic of the Philippines|1936}}<br>{{small|(1946\u20131948)}}\n|branch={{army|United States}}<br>\n[[Philippine Division]]<br>\n[[24th Field Artillery Regiment (United States)|24th Field Artillery Regiment]]<br>\n[[25th Field Artillery Regiment (United States)|25th Field Artillery Regiment]]<br>\n[[26th Cavalry Regiment (PS)]]<br>\n[[31st Infantry Regiment (United States)|31st Infantry Regiment]]<br>\n[[43d Infantry Regiment (PS)]]<br>\n[[44th Infantry Regiment (United States)|44th Infantry Regiment]] <br>\n[[45th Infantry Regiment (PS)]]<br>\n[[57th Infantry Regiment (PS)]]<br>\n[[91st Coast Artillery (United States)|91st Coast Artillery]] <br>\n[[92nd Coast Artillery (United States)|92nd Coast Artillery Regiment]]<br>\n|type=\n|role=\n|size=\n|command_structure=\n|garrison=\n|garrison_label=\n|nickname=\n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=red and gold\n|colors_label=\n|march=\n|mascot= [[Carabao]]\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles=[[Philippine\u2013American War]]<br>[[Moro Rebellion]]<br>[[Palawan|Palawan Uprising]]<br>[[World War II]]\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|disbanded=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|commander1=\n|commander1_label=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|commander3=\n|commander3_label=\n|notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=\n|identification_symbol_label=\n|identification_symbol_2=\n|identification_symbol_2_label=\n|identification_symbol_3=\n|identification_symbol_3_label=\n|identification_symbol_4=\n|identification_symbol_4_label=\n}}\n[[File:FortMcKinley.jpg|thumb|220px|Philippine Scouts at [[Fort William McKinley]] firing a [[37 mm Gun M3|37mm]] anti-tank gun in training.]]\n\nThe '''Philippine Scouts''' ([[Filipino language|Filipino]]: ''Maghahanap ng Pilipinas'' or ''Hukbong Maghahanap ng Pilipinas'') was a military organization of the [[United States Army]] from 1901 until after the end of [[World War II]]. These troops were generally [[Filipinos]] and [[Filipino-Americans]] assigned to the [[United States Army]] [[Philippine Department]], under the command of [[white American]] [[commissioned officer]]s (though a handful of Filipino Americans received commissions from the [[United States Military Academy]]). Philippine Scout units were given the suffix \"'''(PS)'''\", to distinguish them from other U.S. Army units.\n\nThe first Scout companies were organized by the US in 1901 to combat the [[Philippine Revolutionary Army]] led at that time by General [[Emilio Aguinaldo]]. In 1919\u20131920, the PS companies were grouped into regiments as part of the [[United States Army|US Army]] and redesignated the [[43d Infantry Regiment (PS)|43d]], [[44th Infantry Regiment (United States)|44th]], [[45th Infantry Regiment (PS)|45th]], and [[57th Infantry Regiment (PS)|57th Infantry Regiments]], plus the [[24th Field Artillery Regiment (United States)|24th]] and [[25th Field Artillery Regiment (United States)|25th Field Artillery Regiments]], the [[26th Cavalry Regiment (PS)]] and the [[91st Coast Artillery (United States)|91st]] and [[92nd Coast Artillery (United States)|92nd Coast Artillery Regiments]]. Service and support formations were also organized as engineer, medical, quartermaster and military police units. The infantry and field artillery regiments were grouped together with the [[31st Infantry Regiment (United States)|U.S. 31st Infantry Regiment]] to form the U.S. Army's [[Philippine Division]]. At this point, the Scouts became the U.S. Army's front line troops in the Pacific.\n\nThe Philippine Department assigned the Scouts to subdue the [[Moro people|Moro tribes]] on the island of Mindanao (see [[Moro rebellion]]), and to establish tranquility throughout the islands. In the 1930s, Philippine Scouts, along with the [[31st Infantry Regiment (United States)|31st Infantry Regiment]], saw action at [[Palawan|Jolo, Palawan]].\n\nPhilippine Scout regiments became the first United States Army units to be in combat during World War II, until the surrender of [[USAFFE]] in May 1942. Even after that some individual soldiers and units refused to surrender and become beginning elements of the [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines#Resistance|resistance to the Japanese occupation]]. Later paroled [[POWs]] would also join the resistance.\n\n==Macabebe Scouts==\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=Macabebe Scouts\n|image=\n|caption=\n|dates=1896\u20131901\n|country={{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Restoration (Spain)|Spain]]<br>{{small|(1896\u20131898)}}<br />{{flag|United States|1896}}<br>{{small|(1898\u20131901)}}\n|allegiance={{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Restoration (Spain)|Kingdom of Spain]]\n* {{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Spanish East Indies]]<br>{{small|(1896\u20131898)}}\n{{flag|United States of America|1896}}\n* {{flagdeco|United States|1896}} [[United States Military Government of the Philippine Islands|Military Government]]<br>{{small|(1899\u20131901)}}\n|branch={{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Spanish Army]] (1896\u20131898)<br>\n{{army|United States}} (1899\u20131901)\n|type= [[Militia]], [[Irregular military|Irregulars]]\n|role= [[military intelligence|intelligence]], [[reconnaissance]]\n|size= 1402 in December 1900<ref name=dum>{{cite web |last=Dumindin |first=Arnaldo |title=Philippine-American War, 1899\u20131902 |url=http://www.filipinoamericanwar.com/thewarrages1899.htm |accessdate=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n|command_structure=\n|garrison=\n|garrison_label=\n|nickname=\n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles=[[Philippine Revolution]]<br>[[Spanish\u2013American War]]<br>[[Philippine\u2013American War]]<br>[[Moro rebellion]]\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|disbanded=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|commander1=\n|commander1_label=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|commander3=\n|commander3_label=\n|notable_commanders=Col. Eugenio Blanco<br>\nGeneral [[Henry Lawton]]<br>\nGeneral [[Frederick Funston]]<br>\nLieutenant [[Matthew A. Batson]]\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=\n|identification_symbol_label=\n|identification_symbol_2=\n|identification_symbol_2_label=\n|identification_symbol_3=\n|identification_symbol_3_label=\n|identification_symbol_4=\n|identification_symbol_4_label=\n}}\n[[File:1902waterboarding.jpg|thumb|A newspaper depiction from 1902 of [[Water cure (torture)|water curing]] by Macabebe Scouts against fellow Filipinos.]]\n[[File:FvfMacabebe9913 28.JPG|thumb|left|125px|Macabebe Scouts monument-memorial ([[Macabebe, Pampanga]]: On April 23, 1901, the Macabebe scouts helped capture Aguinaldo in [[Palanan, Isabela]]).]]\n\nNative guides and a small number of former [[Spanish Army]] [[militia]] members from [[Macabebe]] that joined U.S. forces commanded by General [[Henry Lawton]] and, after authorization by General [[Elwell Otis]], initially two, and later five companies of Macabebe Scouts were formed on September 10, 1899<ref name=ore>{{cite news |last=Orejas |first=Tonette |title=They were fierce, loyal soldiers |newspaper=[[The Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |date=10 June 2014 |url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/610251/they-were-fierce-loyal-soldiers |accessdate=30 May 2018}}</ref> under Lieutenant [[Matthew A. Batson]].<ref name=Coffman1977p68p72>{{harvnb|Coffman|1977|pp=68, 72}}.</ref> The Macabebes proved themselves reliable over the next two months, and Batson formed five companies of 128 men each; all veterans of service in the militia. In retaliation, Aguinaldo's forces under the command of Col. Agapito Bonzon burned the town of Macabebe and massacred 300 of its residents on June 26, 1898.<ref name=ore /> Batson's Macabebe companies saw combat against Aguinaldo's forces beginning in October 1899, after which they were reorganized into \"The Squadron of Philippine Cavalry, U.S. Volunteers\" on June 1, 1900<ref name=dum /> and enlisted as [[Irregular military|irregulars]]. The Macabebes won lasting notability in the operation under General [[Frederick Funston]] to capture General Aguinaldo.<ref>{{Harvnb|Garc\u00eda|Rodr\u00edguez|2001|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=l533SkJ2VCkC&pg=PA95 95]}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Philippine Scouts 1905.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Formation of Philippine Scouts in 1905.]]\n[[File:Scouts2jf.JPG|thumb|right|125px|The marker ([[Macabebe, Pampanga]] downtown).]]\n\nIn 1901, on the Army's recommendation, U.S. President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] authorized the formation of a unified native Scouts organization. The Army activated this Native Scouts force in October 1901 by integrating 50 local companies into a single force of 5,000 men.<ref>{{Harvnb|Garc\u00eda|Rodr\u00edguez|2001|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=l533SkJ2VCkC&pg=PA97 97\u201398]}}.</ref> Over the next ten years, the Scouts won accolades from their American commanders which contributed to their survival as a unit.<ref>{{Harvnb|Garc\u00eda|Rodr\u00edguez|2001|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=l533SkJ2VCkC&pg=PA99 99]}}.</ref>\n\n==Philippine Scouts and U.S. Army Forces in the Far East (USAFFE)==\nOn July 26, 1941, in preparation for the coming war, President Roosevelt called [[General Douglas MacArthur]] back to active duty and put him in charge of a new military organization: The United States Army Forces in the Far East ([[USAFFE]]). MacArthur took command of all military forces in the Philippines except the U.S. Navy's [[Asiatic Fleet]]. The [[Philippine Division]], [[Philippine Department]] and all other Philippine Scout units were included in USAFFE, as was the U.S. Army's [[United States Far East Air Force|Far East Air Force]] (FEAF). At the time of USAFFE's formation, the unit consisted of 22,532 troops, of which 11,972 were Philippine Scouts.\n\nOf the 22,532 troops, 10,473 were members of the Philippine Division, itself containing 2,552 Americans and 7,921 Filipinos. All of the division's enlisted men, with the exception of the [[31st Infantry Regiment (United States)|31st Infantry Regiment]] and some of the [[Military Police Corps (United States)|military police]] and headquarters troops, were Philippine Scouts.\n\n==Filipino Officers within the Philippine Division, July 1941==\nIn 1910, the U.S. Army began sending one outstanding Filipino soldier per year to West Point. Among these cadets were [[Vicente Lim]] (USMA, Class of 1914),<ref name=Braden1707>{{harvnb|Braden|1920|p=[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=SSHcAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Vicente%20Lim%22&pg=PA1707 1707]}}.</ref> [[Fidel Segundo|Fidel V. Segundo]] (1917),<ref name=Braden1939>{{harvnb|Braden|1920|p=[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=SSHcAAAAMAAJ&dq=Segundo+Ventura&pg=PA1939 1939]}}.</ref> Pastor Martelino (1920),<ref name=Braden2146>{{harvnb|Braden|1920|p=[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=SSHcAAAAMAAJ&dq=Pastor+Martelino&pg=PA2146 2146]}}.</ref> and at least five others.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.westpointaog.org/file/history/International-Graduates.pdf |title=International Graduates |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher=West Point Association of Graduates |access-date=15 May 2018}}</ref> By 1941 some of these men had risen to the rank of senior officers, and some transferred to the Philippine Army when the [[Philippine Commonwealth]] began to build up its own forces in 1937. In July 1941, there were fifteen Filipino Scout officers within the [[Philippine Department|Philippine Division]]. Two were in the Headquarters, two were amongst the Special Troops, three in the [[45th Infantry Regiment (PS)]], one in the [[57th Infantry Regiment (PS)]], five in the [[24th Field Artillery Regiment (PS)]], one in the [[12th Quartermaster Regiment (PS)]], and one in the [[14th Engineer Regiment (PS)]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Strength of the Philippine Division, July 31, 1941<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/5-2/5-2_2.htm|title=The Fall of the Philippines|chapter=Chapter II. U.S. Army Forces, Far East|chapter-url=http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/5-2/5-2_2.htm|author=Louis Morton|editor=Kent Roberts Greenfield|publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]]|year=1953}}.</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Unit\n! rowspan=2 | Total\n! rowspan=2 | Officers\n! colspan=3 | Enlisted\n|-\n! Total\n! American\n! Filipino\n|-\n| All Units || 10,473 || 516{{ref label|scoutmanning|a|a}} || 9,957 || 2,036 || 7,921\n|-\n| Hq and Hq Co || 181 || 30 || 151 || 4 || 147\n|-\n| Special Troops || 5 || 5 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 31st Infantry || 2,100 || 114 || 1,986 || 1,986 || 0\n|-\n| 45th Infantry || 2,265 || 117 || 2,148 || 1 || 2,147\n|-\n| 57th Infantry || 2,279 || 118 || 2,161 || 0 || 2,161\n|-\n| 23rd FA Regt || 401 || 10 || 391 || 0 || 804\n|-\n| 24th FA Regt || 843 || 39 || 804 || 0 || 804\n|-\n| 12th MP Co || 136 || 5 || 131 || 5 || 86\n|-\n|12th QM Regt || 592 || 18 || 574 || 0 || 574\n|-\n| 12th Ord Co || 142 || 3 || 139 || 0 || 139\n|-\n| 12th Sig regt || 227 || 10 || 217 || 0 || 217\n|-\n|4th Vet Co || 11 || 1 || 10 || 0 || 10\n|}\n:{{small|{{note label|scoutmanning|a|a}}Includes 15 Philippine Scout officers: 2 Hq, 2 Sp Trs, 3 45th Inf, 1 57th Inf, 5 24th FA Regt, 1 12th QM Regt, and 1 14th Engr.}}\n:{{small|Source: Phil Dept, Machine Rcds Unit Station Strength and Misc., Officers and Enlisted Men, Jul 41.}}\n\n==World War II==\n[[File:26th Cavalry PI Scouts moving into Pozorrubio.jpg|thumb|220px|26th Cavalry moving into Pozorrubio pass a [[M3 Stuart|General Stuart light tank, M3]] in 1942.]]\n\nOn December 7, 1941, (December 8, 1941 local time in Asia), Imperial Japanese forces attacked the U.S. Navy's [[United States Pacific Fleet|Pacific Fleet]] at Pearl Harbor, bombed the U.S. Army's [[Far East Air Force (United States)|Far East Air Force]] at [[Clark Field]] in the Philippines, attacked [[British Hong Kong]], and landed troops on the shores of [[British Malaya]], simultaneously. Over the next three months the Japanese Army marched through [[Southeast Asia]], and by March 1942 the Japanese had completely overrun every country and island in the western Pacific\u2014except the Philippines.\n\nOn the [[Bataan Peninsula]] of [[Luzon Island]], the Philippine Scouts, a few U.S. Army National Guard units, and ten divisions of poorly equipped, almost untrained [[Philippine Army]] soldiers held out against the Japanese. Survivors of the [[Battle of Bataan]], to a man, describe the Philippine Scouts as the backbone of the American defense there. President Franklin Roosevelt awarded the U.S. Army\u2019s first three [[Medal of Honor|Medals of Honor]] of World War II to Philippine Scouts: to Sergeant [[Jose Calugas]] for action at Culis, Bataan on January 6, 1942, to Lieutenant [[Alexander R. Nininger]] for action near Abucay, Bataan on January 12, and to Lieutenant [[Willibald C. Bianchi]] for action near Bagac, Bataan on February 3, 1942.\n\nWith the U.S. Navy at [[Pearl Harbor]] in shambles, and the Japanese Navy blockading the Philippines, there was no way to send adequate amounts of food, medicine, ammunition or reinforcements to Bataan. Early in the campaign, in January 1942, General MacArthur ordered that his forces be fed one-half daily rations because the USAFFE food-stocks on Bataan were insufficient for the planned six-month siege. Such a diet did not provide enough calories for men working and fighting in the tropical heat of the Philippines' Dry Season. Nonetheless, the Scouts and the other soldiers held out for more than four months without adequate food or medicine, while malaria, dysentery and malnutrition ravaged their ranks, and Japanese attacks drove them further down the [[Bataan Peninsula]]. In the midst of the [[Battle of Bataan]], on 11 March 1942, U.S. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] ordered General [[Douglas MacArthur]] spirited out of the Philippines by PT boat and airplane.\n\n==Prisoners of war==\nThe [[Battle of Bataan]] ended on April 9, 1942, when [[Edward P. King|Major General Edward P. King, Jr.]], surrendered rather than see any more of his starving, diseased men slaughtered by the advancing enemy. At that point 70,000 men became [[Prisoners of War]]: about 16,000 Americans and 54,000 Filipinos. Japanese soldiers marched the emaciated Scouts, American soldiers, and Philippine Army men sixty-five miles up the Bataan Peninsula's East Road on the notorious \"March of Death,\" the [[Bataan Death March]]. During the March, Japanese guards shot or bayoneted between 7,000 and 10,000 men who fell, attempted to escape, or just stopped to quench their thirst at roadside spigots or puddles. They also beat and sometimes killed Filipino civilians who attempted to give food and water to the POWs, and at times flashed the \"V\" for \"Victory\" hand-gesture to the defeated soldiers along the length of the Death March. The March ended at the railroad head in San Fernando, Pampanga province. There the POWs were forced into overcrowded \"40 and 10\" railroad cars, which only had enough room for them to sit down in shifts on the final leg of the trip to Capas, Tarlac province. At Capas they were herded into Camp O'Donnell, a former Philippine Army training camp, which was to be their prison camp.\n\nAt [[Camp O'Donnell]] the Japanese crammed all 60,000 survivors into a Philippine Army camp designed to accommodate 10,000 men. There, the Japanese commander greeted each new group of arrivals with the discouraging \"Goddamn you to Hell\" speech in his native language, and assured the men that they were \"captives,\" not Prisoners of War, and would be treated as such. There was little running water, sparse food, no medical care, and only slit trenches for sanitation. The heat was intolerable, flies rose out of the latrines and covered the prisoner's food, and malaria, dysentery, beriberi and a host of other diseases swept through the crowds of men. They began to die at the rate of four hundred per day.\n\nFrom September through December 1942, the Japanese gradually paroled the surviving Philippine Scouts and other Filipino soldiers to their families and to the mayors of their hometowns. But by the time Camp O'Donnell closed in January 1943, after eight months of operation, 26,000 of the 50,000 Filipino [[Prisoners of War]] had died there.\n\nThe Japanese transferred the American prisoners to [[Cabanatuan]], Nueva Ecija province, where conditions were only marginally better. But as U.S. forces pulled closer to the Philippines in 1944, they [[Hell ship|evacuated]] the healthiest American prisoners to [[Japan]] and [[Manchuria]], for use as slave laborers. Thousands of men were crammed into the dark holds of cargo ships so tightly that they could not sit or lay down. Again, food and water were scarce, sanitary facilities were non-existent, and the heat in the closed holds of the ships was unbearable. Men suffocated to death standing up. The Japanese ships were unmarked and some of them were torpedoed by American submarines. More of the men died of malnutrition and exposure in the work camps. By the time Japan surrendered and the U.S. and Filipino Army liberated the Bataan Prisoners of War, two-thirds of the American prisoners had died in Japanese custody.\n\n==Liberation and the \"New\" Scouts==\nDuring the Japanese occupation of the Philippines an extensive Filipino [[guerrilla]] movement sprang up. In some cases the guerrilla units were led by escaped American officers (e.g., [[Wendell Fertig]]) and often included \"paroled\" Philippine Scout and Philippine Commonwealth Army soldiers, along with civilian members of the Philippine underground. As MacArthur\u2019s forces, supported by the guerrillas, liberated the [[Philippine Islands]], the surviving Philippine Scouts stepped forward and rejoined the U.S. Army. The Filipino guerrillas joined them, and the U.S. Army set up new Philippine Scout units, reconstituting the old Philippine Division as the [[Philippine Division (United States)|12th Infantry Division]]. Subordinate units included the [[43rd Infantry Regiment (PS)|43rd]], [[44th Infantry Regiment (PS)|44th]] and [[45th Infantry Regiment (PS)|45th Infantry Regiments]] (PS); [[23rd Field Artillery (PS)|23rd]], [[24th Field Artillery (PS)|24th]] and [[88th Field Artillery (PS)|88th Field Artillery]] (PS) Battalions; [[56th Engineer Battalion (PS)]] and the [[57th Infantry Regiment (PS)]]. The \"New Scouts\" actively participated in combat against the Japanese Army in north [[Luzon]], served as [[military police]] to restore order and help locate pockets of escaped Japanese in the south, and served as occupation forces on [[Okinawa]]. As planning for the invasion of Japan progressed, the Philippine Scouts were included in the invasion forces, and were selected to become part of the occupying force once Japan was defeated.\n\nAfter Japan surrendered in August 1945, the United States granted the Republic of the Philippines full independence on July 4, 1946. At that point the ethnically Filipino Philippine Scouts held a unique status in U.S. military history: they were soldiers in the regular U.S. Army, but now they were citizens of a foreign country. To solve this dilemma, the United States offered the Filipinos in the Philippine Scouts full [[U.S. citizenship]]. Many of the surviving Scouts, perhaps around 1,000, accepted, and the Army transferred them to other units to finish their military careers.\n\nWith the consent of the Philippine government, Congress approved the maintenance of 50,000 Philippine Scouts. Under Major General Hibbs, Philippine Division as the 12th Infantry Division (PS) was reconstituted. Unlike its previous organization enlisted personnel of the division were exclusively Philippine Scouts. The War Department also proposed organizing a second Philippine Scout division, the [[14th Infantry Division (United States)|14th]], but never did so.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alexander M. Bielakowski Ph.D.|title=Ethnic and Racial Minorities in the U.S. Military: An Encyclopedia &#91;2 volumes&#93;|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w_Mqj6UuRgQC&pg=PT157|date=11 January 2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-428-3|pages=157\u2013}}</ref> In the end [[Harry S. Truman|President Truman]] disbanded the Philippine Scouts as an official element of the United States Army, and all of their unit colors were retired in 1947,<ref>{{cite book |title=MANEUVER AND FIREPOWER |last=Wilson |first=John B. |author2=Jeffrey J. Clarke |year=1998 |publisher=[[Center of Military History]], [[United States Army]] |location=Washington D.C. |page=212 |url=http://www.history.army.mil/catalog/pubs/60/60-14.html|chapter=Chapter VIII: An Interlude of Peace|chapterurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027171421/http://www.history.army.mil/books/Lineage/M-F/chapter8.htm |accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and finally disbanded in December 1948.<ref>{{cite book |title=World War 2 Pacific island guide |last=Rottman |first=Godron L. |year=2002 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |location=Westport, Connecticut |isbn=978-0-313-31395-0 |page=318 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ChyilRml0hcC&lpg=PA318&dq=guerrilla%20Philippine%20liberation%20fighting%20Japanese&pg=PA318#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nMany of the former Philippine Scouts went on to serve the United States in military careers of twenty and more years, campaigning in the [[Korean War]], the build-up to the planned invasion of Cuba during the October 1962 Missile Crisis, the [[Vietnam War]], and the Cold War. Children of the Scouts (known as \"Army Soup\" in pre-World War II Fort William McKinley days) sometimes carried on their fathers' military traditions and also became US Army soldiers and Marines. Two Philippine Scout children even earned the stars of US Army generals: Lt. General [[Edward Soriano]] and Major General [[Antonio M. Taguba]]. A third, Brig. General [[Oscar Hilman]], a native of Washington state and an armor officer who had started out as an enlisted man, earned his star in a long career in the Army National Guard.\n\nUnlike other non-citizen veterans, veterans of the Philippine Division and other Filipinos who fought as part of the [[USAFFE]] were never granted citizenship. Since 1993, various bills have been introduced to the [[United States Congress]] under the name [[Filipino Veterans Fairness Act]] to rectify this. However, this was a complicated matter as after the liberation of the Philippines members of the Philippine Scouts were offered enlistments and in some applicable cases commissions in the US Army and subsequent citizenship. Large numbers of \"old\" Philippine Scouts (those enlisting before or during World War II) took advantage of this. However, most \"new\" Philippine Scouts (those recruited following the war, mostly for occupation duty on Okinawa and elsewhere) were not offered citizenship. Language similar to the aforementioned proposed legislation was inserted by the Senate into the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]]<ref>{{cite news |first=Rick|last=Maze |title=Senate puts Filipino vet pensions in stimulus |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2009/01/military_filipinoscouts_stimulus_012909w/ |format=News article |work=Army Times |date=2008-01-29|accessdate=2009-01-30 |quote=Buried inside the Senate bill, which includes tax cuts and new spending initiatives intended to create jobs in the U.S., the Filipino payment was inserted at the urging of Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, the new chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee and a longtime supporter of monthly pensions for World War II Filipino veterans.}}</ref> which was signed into law. This provided a one-time payment to those veterans who are recognized as being soldiers or recognized guerrilla members by the United States or their surviving spouse. Even this, however, falls far short of the benefits available to similar veterans of other units.\n\nIn 2012, a [[documentary film]] named ''Forgotten Soldiers'' was produced by Donald A. Pata, with the help of Associate Instructor Chris Schaefer of the [[University of Utah]], and narrated by [[Lou Diamond Phillips]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Forgotten Soldiers: A Film Recognizing the Bravery and Courage of WWII's Philippine Scouts |author=Malou Liwanag-Bledsoe |url=http://www.asianjournal.com/aj-magazine/something-filipino/17559-forgotten-soldiers-a-film-recognizing-the-bravery-and-courage-of-wwiis-philippine-scouts.html |newspaper=Asian Journal |date=3 October 2012 |accessdate=5 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128075437/http://asianjournal.com/aj-magazine/something-filipino/17559-forgotten-soldiers-a-film-recognizing-the-bravery-and-courage-of-wwiis-philippine-scouts.html |archivedate=28 January 2013 }}</ref> The film received awards from the City of [[Los Angeles]], the [[California Senate]], [[County of Los Angeles]], and at the [[Beloit International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news |title=City of LA recognizes Donald Plata for 'Forgotten' Soldiers |url=http://www.asianjournal.com/community/community-news/17827-city-of-la-recognizes-donald-plata-for-forgotten-soldiers-.html |newspaper=Asian Journal |date=19 October 2012 |accessdate=5 May 2013 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Philippine Scouts==\n* [[Vicente Barros]] \u2013 Major, U.S. Army, the only Filipino officer among the ranks of Americans during the formation of the [[Philippine National Guard]] in 1917.<ref>{{cite news |title=THE CORNERSTONE OF PHILIPPINE INDEPENDENCE: A Narrative Of Seven Years |author=Francis Burton Harrison |url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/AFJ2343.0001.001/192 |pages=166 |publisher=Kessinger Publishing, LLC |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=17 April 2014}}<br />{{cite book|author=Francis Burton Harrison|title=The Corner-stone of Philippine Independence|url=https://archive.org/details/cornerstonephil00harrgoog|year=1922|publisher=Century Company|page=[https://archive.org/details/cornerstonephil00harrgoog/page/n196 166]}}</ref> Became advisor to the Philippine Commonwealth militia, the National Volunteers of the Philippines in 1935.<ref>{{cite news |title=THE PHILIPPINE ARMY, 1935-1942 |author=Ricardo Trota Jose |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kGocnp15GQ8C&pg=PA13&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=4#v=onepage&q=barros&f=false |pages=21 |publisher=Ateneo de Manila University Press (1992) |accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Willibald C. Bianchi]] \u2013 [[First Lieutenant#United States|First Lieutenant]], [[United States Army|U.S. Army]]. [[Medal of Honor]] recipient, 45th Infantry Regiment\n* [[Jose Calugas]] \u2013 [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]], U.S. Army. Medal of Honor recipient, 88th Field Artillery Regiment\n* [[Eddie Garcia]] \u2013 unknown rank, unknown unit. Actor, previously a Philippine Scout in Okinawa.<ref>{{cite news |last=Layug |first=Margaret Claire |date=22 June 2019 |title=Eddie Garcia honored by Philippine Army in memorial service |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/698592/eddie-garcia-honored-by-philippine-army-in-memorial-service/story/ |work=GMA News |location=Philippines |access-date=3 July 2019 }}</ref>\n* [[Louis C. Mosher]] \u2013 First Lieutenant, U.S. Army. Medal of Honor recipient\n* [[Alexander R. Nininger]] \u2013 [[Second Lieutenant#United States|Second Lieutenant]], U.S. Army. First Medal of Honor recipient in World War II, 57th Infantry Regiment\n* [[Jos\u00e9 B. N\u00edsperos]] \u2013 [[Private First Class#United States|Private First Class]], U.S. Army. First Asian Medal of Honor recipient, 34th Company\n* [[Juan Pajota]] \u2013 Captain, U.S. Army, 45th Infantry Regiment\n* [[Edwin Ramsey]] \u2013 First Lieutenant, U.S. Army. Led last horse cavalry charge in U.S. military history, 26th Cavalry Regiment\n* [[Benigno G. Tabora]] \u2013 [[Sergeant major#United States Army|Sergeant Major]], U.S. Army. [[Purple Heart]] recipient\n* [[Miguel White]] \u2013 Lieutenant, [[Philippine Commonwealth Army|Philippine Army]]. Olympian, previously a Philippine Scout.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mariano Villarin|title=We Remember Bataan and Corregidor: The Story of the American & Filipino Defenders of Bataan and Corregidor and Their Captivity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wj4gAAAAMAAJ|year=1990|publisher=Gateway Press|isbn=978-0-9626127-0-1|page=53}}</ref>\n* [[Teofilo Yldefonso]] \u2013 Sergeant, U.S. Army. Olympian, [[57th Infantry Regiment (United States)|57th Infantry Regiment]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Viloria |first=Barry |date= 8 September 2016 |title=What makes the first Filipino Olympics medalist a \u2018hero\u2019 |url=https://sports.abs-cbn.com/sportslifestyle/news/2016/09/08/what-makes-first-filipino-olympics-medalist-hero-15317 |work=ABS-CBN |location=Philippines |access-date=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alamo Scouts]]\n* [[Apache Scouts]]\n* [[Eskimo Scouts]]\n* [[Military history of Asian Americans]]\n* [[Military History of the Philippines]]\n* [[Military History of the United States]]\n* [[Navajo Scouts]]\n* [[Philippine Scout Mutiny]]\n* [[United States Army Indian Scouts]]\n\n==Bibliography and references==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Braden|first=Charles|editor=Wirt Robinson|title=Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U.S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y.: from its establishment, in 1802, to 1890, with the early history of the United States Military Academy |year=1920 |publisher=Houghton, Mifflin |location=University of Michigan |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SSHcAAAAMAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Coffman|first=Edward M.|title=Batson of the Philippine Scouts|year=1977|volume=VII|issue=3|journal=Journal of the US Army War College|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Rodao Garc\u00eda|author-link1=Florentino Rodao|first1=Florentino |last2=Rodr\u00edguez|first2=Felice Noelle |title=The Philippine Revolution of 1896: Ordinary Lives in Extraordinary Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l533SkJ2VCkC|year=2001|publisher=Ateneo de Manila University Press|isbn=978-971-550-386-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Knox|first=Donald |title=Death March: The Survivors of Bataan|url=https://archive.org/details/deathmarchsurviv00knox|url-access=registration|year=1981|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|isbn=978-0-15-124094-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Linn|first=Brian McAllister |authorlink=Brian McAllister Linn|title=Guardians of Empire: The U.S. Army and the Pacific, 1902-1940|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zEOtgqPEkgwC|year=1999|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=978-0-8078-4815-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Morton|first=|title=The Fall of the Philippines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1AJgPwAACAAJ|year=2004|publisher=University Press of the Pacific|isbn=978-1-4102-1696-0}}\n* {{cite book|author=Philippine Scouts Heritage Society|title=The Philippine Scouts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Def9NwAACAAJ|year=1996|publisher=The Society}}\n* {{cite book|last=Olson|first=John E. |title=O'Donnell, Andersonville of the Pacific|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XaOEAAAAIAAJ|year=1985|publisher=J.E. Olson}}\n* {{cite book|author=United States War Dept|title=Annual Reports of the Secretary of War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QjhKQgAACAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Books LLC|isbn=978-1-4588-1628-3}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Philippine Scouts}}\n* [http://www.philippine-scouts.org/ Philippine Scouts Heritage Society]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110624063024/http://www.army.mil/asianpacificsoldiers/history/phillipineScouts.html Philippine Scouts on United States Army website]\n\n[[Category:Military history of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:20th-century military history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Philippines during World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Army in World War II]]\n[[Category:Philippine\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:Filipino-American history]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:United States military in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:History of the Philippines (1898\u20131946)]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the military unit|the youth movement|Boy Scouts of the Philippines}}\n{{More footnotes|date=May 2008}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=Philippine Scouts\n|image=[[File:12th Infantry Division SSI.svg|225px]]\n|caption=Philippine Scouts [[shoulder sleeve insignia]] from 1921\u20131947 was the head of the [[carabao]] ([[water buffalo]]) which symbolized the Philippines. The colors red and gold represented the islands' Spanish colonial roots.\n|dates=1901\u20131948\n|country={{flag|United States|1912}}<br>{{flag|Philippines|1936}}\n|allegiance={{flag|United States of America|1912}}<br>{{small|(1901\u20131946)}}\n* {{flagdeco|Philippines|1919}} [[Insular Government (Philippines)|Insular Government]]<br>{{small|(1901\u20131935)}}\n* {{flag|Commonwealth of the Philippines}}<br>{{small|(1935\u20131946)}}\n{{flag|Republic of the Philippines|1936}}<br>{{small|(1946\u20131948)}}\n|branch={{army|United States}}<br>\n[[Philippine Division]]<br>\n[[24th Field Artillery Regiment (United States)|24th Field Artillery Regiment]]<br>\n[[25th Field Artillery Regiment (United States)|25th Field Artillery Regiment]]<br>\n[[26th Cavalry Regiment (PS)]]<br>\n[[31st Infantry Regiment (United States)|31st Infantry Regiment]]<br>\n[[43d Infantry Regiment (PS)]]<br>\n[[44th Infantry Regiment (United States)|44th Infantry Regiment]] <br>\n[[45th Infantry Regiment (PS)]]<br>\n[[57th Infantry Regiment (PS)]]<br>\n[[91st Coast Artillery (United States)|91st Coast Artillery]] <br>\n[[92nd Coast Artillery (United States)|92nd Coast Artillery Regiment]]<br>\n|type=\n|role=\n|size=\n|command_structure=\n|garrison=\n|garrison_label=\n|nickname=\n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=red and gold\n|colors_label=\n|march=\n|mascot= [[Carabao]]\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles=[[Philippine\u2013American War]]<br>[[Moro Rebellion]]<br>[[Palawan|Palawan Uprising]]<br>[[World War II]]\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|disbanded=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|commander1=\n|commander1_label=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|commander3=\n|commander3_label=\n|notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=\n|identification_symbol_label=\n|identification_symbol_2=\n|identification_symbol_2_label=\n|identification_symbol_3=\n|identification_symbol_3_label=\n|identification_symbol_4=\n|identification_symbol_4_label=\n}}\n[[File:FortMcKinley.jpg|thumb|220px|Philippine Scouts at [[Fort William McKinley]] firing a [[37 mm Gun M3|37mm]] anti-tank gun in training.]]\n\nThe '''Philippine Scouts''' ([[Filipino language|Filipino]]: ''Maghahanap ng Pilipinas'' or ''Hukbong Maghahanap ng Pilipinas'') was a military organization of the [[United States Army]] from 1901 until after the end of [[World War II]]. These troops were generally [[Filipinos]] and [[Filipino-Americans]] assigned to the [[United States Army]] [[Philippine Department]], under the command of [[white American]] [[commissioned officer]]s (though a handful of Filipino Americans received commissions from the [[United States Military Academy]]). Philippine Scout units were given the suffix \"'''(PS)'''\", to distinguish them from other U.S. Army units.\n\nThe first Scout companies were organized by the US in 1901 to combat the [[Philippine Revolutionary Army]] led at that time by General [[Emilio Aguinaldo]]. In 1919\u20131920, the PS companies were grouped into regiments as part of the [[United States Army|US Army]] and redesignated the [[43d Infantry Regiment (PS)|43d]], [[44th Infantry Regiment (United States)|44th]], [[45th Infantry Regiment (PS)|45th]], and [[57th Infantry Regiment (PS)|57th Infantry Regiments]], plus the [[24th Field Artillery Regiment (United States)|24th]] and [[25th Field Artillery Regiment (United States)|25th Field Artillery Regiments]], the [[26th Cavalry Regiment (PS)]] and the [[91st Coast Artillery (United States)|91st]] and [[92nd Coast Artillery (United States)|92nd Coast Artillery Regiments]]. Service and support formations were also organized as engineer, medical, quartermaster and military police units. The infantry and field artillery regiments were grouped together with the [[31st Infantry Regiment (United States)|U.S. 31st Infantry Regiment]] to form the U.S. Army's [[Philippine Division]]. At this point, the Scouts became the U.S. Army's front line troops in the Pacific.\n\nThe Philippine Department assigned the Scouts to subdue the [[Moro people|Moro tribes]] on the island of Mindanao (see [[Moro rebellion]]), and to establish tranquility throughout the islands. In the 1930s, Philippine Scouts, along with the [[31st Infantry Regiment (United States)|31st Infantry Regiment]], saw action at [[Palawan|Jolo, Palawan]].\n\nPhilippine Scout regiments became the first United States Army units to be in combat during World War II, until the surrender of [[USAFFE]] in May 1942. Even after that some individual soldiers and units refused to surrender and become beginning elements of the [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines#Resistance|resistance to the Japanese occupation]]. Later paroled [[POWs]] would also join the resistance.\n\n==Macabebe Scouts==\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=Macabebe Scouts\n|image=\n|caption=\n|dates=1896\u20131901\n|country={{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Restoration (Spain)|Spain]]<br>{{small|(1896\u20131898)}}<br />{{flag|United States|1896}}<br>{{small|(1898\u20131901)}}\n|allegiance={{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Restoration (Spain)|Kingdom of Spain]]\n* {{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Spanish East Indies]]<br>{{small|(1896\u20131898)}}\n{{flag|United States of America|1896}}\n* {{flagdeco|United States|1896}} [[United States Military Government of the Philippine Islands|Military Government]]<br>{{small|(1899\u20131901)}}\n|branch={{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Spanish Army]] (1896\u20131898)<br>\n{{army|United States}} (1899\u20131901)\n|type= [[Irregular military|Irregulars]]\n|role= [[military intelligence|intelligence]], [[reconnaissance]]\n|size= 1402 in December 1900<ref name=dum>{{cite web |last=Dumindin |first=Arnaldo |title=Philippine-American War, 1899\u20131902 |url=http://www.filipinoamericanwar.com/thewarrages1899.htm |accessdate=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n|command_structure=\n|garrison=\n|garrison_label=\n|nickname=\n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles=[[Philippine Revolution]]<br>[[Spanish\u2013American War]]<br>[[Philippine\u2013American War]]<br>[[Moro rebellion]]\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|disbanded=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|commander1=\n|commander1_label=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|commander3=\n|commander3_label=\n|notable_commanders=Col. Eugenio Blanco<br>\nGeneral [[Henry Lawton]]<br>\nGeneral [[Frederick Funston]]<br>\nLieutenant [[Matthew A. Batson]]\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=\n|identification_symbol_label=\n|identification_symbol_2=\n|identification_symbol_2_label=\n|identification_symbol_3=\n|identification_symbol_3_label=\n|identification_symbol_4=\n|identification_symbol_4_label=\n}}\n[[File:1902waterboarding.jpg|thumb|A newspaper depiction from 1902 of [[Water cure (torture)|water curing]] by Macabebe Scouts against fellow Filipinos.]]\n[[File:FvfMacabebe9913 28.JPG|thumb|left|125px|Macabebe Scouts monument-memorial ([[Macabebe, Pampanga]]: On April 23, 1901, the Macabebe scouts helped capture Aguinaldo in [[Palanan, Isabela]]).]]\n\nNative guides and a small number of former [[Spanish Army]] [[militia]] members from [[Macabebe]] that joined U.S. forces commanded by General [[Henry Lawton]] and, after authorization by General [[Elwell Otis]], initially two, and later five companies of Macabebe Scouts were formed on September 10, 1899<ref name=ore>{{cite news |last=Orejas |first=Tonette |title=They were fierce, loyal soldiers |newspaper=[[The Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |date=10 June 2014 |url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/610251/they-were-fierce-loyal-soldiers |accessdate=30 May 2018}}</ref> under Lieutenant [[Matthew A. Batson]].<ref name=Coffman1977p68p72>{{harvnb|Coffman|1977|pp=68, 72}}.</ref> The Macabebes proved themselves reliable over the next two months, and Batson formed five companies of 128 men each; all veterans of service in the militia. In retaliation, Aguinaldo's forces under the command of Col. Agapito Bonzon burned the town of Macabebe and massacred 300 of its residents on June 26, 1898.<ref name=ore /> Batson's Macabebe companies saw combat against Aguinaldo's forces beginning in October 1899, after which they were reorganized into \"The Squadron of Philippine Cavalry, U.S. Volunteers\" on June 1, 1900<ref name=dum /> and enlisted as [[Irregular military|irregulars]]. The Macabebes won lasting notability in the operation under General [[Frederick Funston]] to capture General Aguinaldo.<ref>{{Harvnb|Garc\u00eda|Rodr\u00edguez|2001|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=l533SkJ2VCkC&pg=PA95 95]}}.</ref>\n\n[[File:Philippine Scouts 1905.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Formation of Philippine Scouts in 1905.]]\n[[File:Scouts2jf.JPG|thumb|right|125px|The marker ([[Macabebe, Pampanga]] downtown).]]\n\nIn 1901, on the Army's recommendation, U.S. President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] authorized the formation of a unified native Scouts organization. The Army activated this Native Scouts force in October 1901 by integrating 50 local companies into a single force of 5,000 men.<ref>{{Harvnb|Garc\u00eda|Rodr\u00edguez|2001|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=l533SkJ2VCkC&pg=PA97 97\u201398]}}.</ref> Over the next ten years, the Scouts won accolades from their American commanders which contributed to their survival as a unit.<ref>{{Harvnb|Garc\u00eda|Rodr\u00edguez|2001|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=l533SkJ2VCkC&pg=PA99 99]}}.</ref>\n\n==Philippine Scouts and U.S. Army Forces in the Far East (USAFFE)==\nOn July 26, 1941, in preparation for the coming war, President Roosevelt called [[General Douglas MacArthur]] back to active duty and put him in charge of a new military organization: The United States Army Forces in the Far East ([[USAFFE]]). MacArthur took command of all military forces in the Philippines except the U.S. Navy's [[Asiatic Fleet]]. The [[Philippine Division]], [[Philippine Department]] and all other Philippine Scout units were included in USAFFE, as was the U.S. Army's [[United States Far East Air Force|Far East Air Force]] (FEAF). At the time of USAFFE's formation, the unit consisted of 22,532 troops, of which 11,972 were Philippine Scouts.\n\nOf the 22,532 troops, 10,473 were members of the Philippine Division, itself containing 2,552 Americans and 7,921 Filipinos. All of the division's enlisted men, with the exception of the [[31st Infantry Regiment (United States)|31st Infantry Regiment]] and some of the [[Military Police Corps (United States)|military police]] and headquarters troops, were Philippine Scouts.\n\n==Filipino Officers within the Philippine Division, July 1941==\nIn 1910, the U.S. Army began sending one outstanding Filipino soldier per year to West Point. Among these cadets were [[Vicente Lim]] (USMA, Class of 1914),<ref name=Braden1707>{{harvnb|Braden|1920|p=[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=SSHcAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Vicente%20Lim%22&pg=PA1707 1707]}}.</ref> [[Fidel Segundo|Fidel V. Segundo]] (1917),<ref name=Braden1939>{{harvnb|Braden|1920|p=[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=SSHcAAAAMAAJ&dq=Segundo+Ventura&pg=PA1939 1939]}}.</ref> Pastor Martelino (1920),<ref name=Braden2146>{{harvnb|Braden|1920|p=[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=SSHcAAAAMAAJ&dq=Pastor+Martelino&pg=PA2146 2146]}}.</ref> and at least five others.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.westpointaog.org/file/history/International-Graduates.pdf |title=International Graduates |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher=West Point Association of Graduates |access-date=15 May 2018}}</ref> By 1941 some of these men had risen to the rank of senior officers, and some transferred to the Philippine Army when the [[Philippine Commonwealth]] began to build up its own forces in 1937. In July 1941, there were fifteen Filipino Scout officers within the [[Philippine Department|Philippine Division]]. Two were in the Headquarters, two were amongst the Special Troops, three in the [[45th Infantry Regiment (PS)]], one in the [[57th Infantry Regiment (PS)]], five in the [[24th Field Artillery Regiment (PS)]], one in the [[12th Quartermaster Regiment (PS)]], and one in the [[14th Engineer Regiment (PS)]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Strength of the Philippine Division, July 31, 1941<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/5-2/5-2_2.htm|title=The Fall of the Philippines|chapter=Chapter II. U.S. Army Forces, Far East|chapter-url=http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/5-2/5-2_2.htm|author=Louis Morton|editor=Kent Roberts Greenfield|publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]]|year=1953}}.</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Unit\n! rowspan=2 | Total\n! rowspan=2 | Officers\n! colspan=3 | Enlisted\n|-\n! Total\n! American\n! Filipino\n|-\n| All Units || 10,473 || 516{{ref label|scoutmanning|a|a}} || 9,957 || 2,036 || 7,921\n|-\n| Hq and Hq Co || 181 || 30 || 151 || 4 || 147\n|-\n| Special Troops || 5 || 5 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 31st Infantry || 2,100 || 114 || 1,986 || 1,986 || 0\n|-\n| 45th Infantry || 2,265 || 117 || 2,148 || 1 || 2,147\n|-\n| 57th Infantry || 2,279 || 118 || 2,161 || 0 || 2,161\n|-\n| 23rd FA Regt || 401 || 10 || 391 || 0 || 804\n|-\n| 24th FA Regt || 843 || 39 || 804 || 0 || 804\n|-\n| 12th MP Co || 136 || 5 || 131 || 5 || 86\n|-\n|12th QM Regt || 592 || 18 || 574 || 0 || 574\n|-\n| 12th Ord Co || 142 || 3 || 139 || 0 || 139\n|-\n| 12th Sig regt || 227 || 10 || 217 || 0 || 217\n|-\n|4th Vet Co || 11 || 1 || 10 || 0 || 10\n|}\n:{{small|{{note label|scoutmanning|a|a}}Includes 15 Philippine Scout officers: 2 Hq, 2 Sp Trs, 3 45th Inf, 1 57th Inf, 5 24th FA Regt, 1 12th QM Regt, and 1 14th Engr.}}\n:{{small|Source: Phil Dept, Machine Rcds Unit Station Strength and Misc., Officers and Enlisted Men, Jul 41.}}\n\n==World War II==\n[[File:26th Cavalry PI Scouts moving into Pozorrubio.jpg|thumb|220px|26th Cavalry moving into Pozorrubio pass a [[M3 Stuart|General Stuart light tank, M3]] in 1942.]]\n\nOn December 7, 1941, (December 8, 1941 local time in Asia), Imperial Japanese forces attacked the U.S. Navy's [[United States Pacific Fleet|Pacific Fleet]] at Pearl Harbor, bombed the U.S. Army's [[Far East Air Force (United States)|Far East Air Force]] at [[Clark Field]] in the Philippines, attacked [[British Hong Kong]], and landed troops on the shores of [[British Malaya]], simultaneously. Over the next three months the Japanese Army marched through [[Southeast Asia]], and by March 1942 the Japanese had completely overrun every country and island in the western Pacific\u2014except the Philippines.\n\nOn the [[Bataan Peninsula]] of [[Luzon Island]], the Philippine Scouts, a few U.S. Army National Guard units, and ten divisions of poorly equipped, almost untrained [[Philippine Army]] soldiers held out against the Japanese. Survivors of the [[Battle of Bataan]], to a man, describe the Philippine Scouts as the backbone of the American defense there. President Franklin Roosevelt awarded the U.S. Army\u2019s first three [[Medal of Honor|Medals of Honor]] of World War II to Philippine Scouts: to Sergeant [[Jose Calugas]] for action at Culis, Bataan on January 6, 1942, to Lieutenant [[Alexander R. Nininger]] for action near Abucay, Bataan on January 12, and to Lieutenant [[Willibald C. Bianchi]] for action near Bagac, Bataan on February 3, 1942.\n\nWith the U.S. Navy at [[Pearl Harbor]] in shambles, and the Japanese Navy blockading the Philippines, there was no way to send adequate amounts of food, medicine, ammunition or reinforcements to Bataan. Early in the campaign, in January 1942, General MacArthur ordered that his forces be fed one-half daily rations because the USAFFE food-stocks on Bataan were insufficient for the planned six-month siege. Such a diet did not provide enough calories for men working and fighting in the tropical heat of the Philippines' Dry Season. Nonetheless, the Scouts and the other soldiers held out for more than four months without adequate food or medicine, while malaria, dysentery and malnutrition ravaged their ranks, and Japanese attacks drove them further down the [[Bataan Peninsula]]. In the midst of the [[Battle of Bataan]], on 11 March 1942, U.S. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] ordered General [[Douglas MacArthur]] spirited out of the Philippines by PT boat and airplane.\n\n==Prisoners of war==\nThe [[Battle of Bataan]] ended on April 9, 1942, when [[Edward P. King|Major General Edward P. King, Jr.]], surrendered rather than see any more of his starving, diseased men slaughtered by the advancing enemy. At that point 70,000 men became [[Prisoners of War]]: about 16,000 Americans and 54,000 Filipinos. Japanese soldiers marched the emaciated Scouts, American soldiers, and Philippine Army men sixty-five miles up the Bataan Peninsula's East Road on the notorious \"March of Death,\" the [[Bataan Death March]]. During the March, Japanese guards shot or bayoneted between 7,000 and 10,000 men who fell, attempted to escape, or just stopped to quench their thirst at roadside spigots or puddles. They also beat and sometimes killed Filipino civilians who attempted to give food and water to the POWs, and at times flashed the \"V\" for \"Victory\" hand-gesture to the defeated soldiers along the length of the Death March. The March ended at the railroad head in San Fernando, Pampanga province. There the POWs were forced into overcrowded \"40 and 10\" railroad cars, which only had enough room for them to sit down in shifts on the final leg of the trip to Capas, Tarlac province. At Capas they were herded into Camp O'Donnell, a former Philippine Army training camp, which was to be their prison camp.\n\nAt [[Camp O'Donnell]] the Japanese crammed all 60,000 survivors into a Philippine Army camp designed to accommodate 10,000 men. There, the Japanese commander greeted each new group of arrivals with the discouraging \"Goddamn you to Hell\" speech in his native language, and assured the men that they were \"captives,\" not Prisoners of War, and would be treated as such. There was little running water, sparse food, no medical care, and only slit trenches for sanitation. The heat was intolerable, flies rose out of the latrines and covered the prisoner's food, and malaria, dysentery, beriberi and a host of other diseases swept through the crowds of men. They began to die at the rate of four hundred per day.\n\nFrom September through December 1942, the Japanese gradually paroled the surviving Philippine Scouts and other Filipino soldiers to their families and to the mayors of their hometowns. But by the time Camp O'Donnell closed in January 1943, after eight months of operation, 26,000 of the 50,000 Filipino [[Prisoners of War]] had died there.\n\nThe Japanese transferred the American prisoners to [[Cabanatuan]], Nueva Ecija province, where conditions were only marginally better. But as U.S. forces pulled closer to the Philippines in 1944, they [[Hell ship|evacuated]] the healthiest American prisoners to [[Japan]] and [[Manchuria]], for use as slave laborers. Thousands of men were crammed into the dark holds of cargo ships so tightly that they could not sit or lay down. Again, food and water were scarce, sanitary facilities were non-existent, and the heat in the closed holds of the ships was unbearable. Men suffocated to death standing up. The Japanese ships were unmarked and some of them were torpedoed by American submarines. More of the men died of malnutrition and exposure in the work camps. By the time Japan surrendered and the U.S. and Filipino Army liberated the Bataan Prisoners of War, two-thirds of the American prisoners had died in Japanese custody.\n\n==Liberation and the \"New\" Scouts==\nDuring the Japanese occupation of the Philippines an extensive Filipino [[guerrilla]] movement sprang up. In some cases the guerrilla units were led by escaped American officers (e.g., [[Wendell Fertig]]) and often included \"paroled\" Philippine Scout and Philippine Commonwealth Army soldiers, along with civilian members of the Philippine underground. As MacArthur\u2019s forces, supported by the guerrillas, liberated the [[Philippine Islands]], the surviving Philippine Scouts stepped forward and rejoined the U.S. Army. The Filipino guerrillas joined them, and the U.S. Army set up new Philippine Scout units, reconstituting the old Philippine Division as the [[Philippine Division (United States)|12th Infantry Division]]. Subordinate units included the [[43rd Infantry Regiment (PS)|43rd]], [[44th Infantry Regiment (PS)|44th]] and [[45th Infantry Regiment (PS)|45th Infantry Regiments]] (PS); [[23rd Field Artillery (PS)|23rd]], [[24th Field Artillery (PS)|24th]] and [[88th Field Artillery (PS)|88th Field Artillery]] (PS) Battalions; [[56th Engineer Battalion (PS)]] and the [[57th Infantry Regiment (PS)]]. The \"New Scouts\" actively participated in combat against the Japanese Army in north [[Luzon]], served as [[military police]] to restore order and help locate pockets of escaped Japanese in the south, and served as occupation forces on [[Okinawa]]. As planning for the invasion of Japan progressed, the Philippine Scouts were included in the invasion forces, and were selected to become part of the occupying force once Japan was defeated.\n\nAfter Japan surrendered in August 1945, the United States granted the Republic of the Philippines full independence on July 4, 1946. At that point the ethnically Filipino Philippine Scouts held a unique status in U.S. military history: they were soldiers in the regular U.S. Army, but now they were citizens of a foreign country. To solve this dilemma, the United States offered the Filipinos in the Philippine Scouts full [[U.S. citizenship]]. Many of the surviving Scouts, perhaps around 1,000, accepted, and the Army transferred them to other units to finish their military careers.\n\nWith the consent of the Philippine government, Congress approved the maintenance of 50,000 Philippine Scouts. Under Major General Hibbs, Philippine Division as the 12th Infantry Division (PS) was reconstituted. Unlike its previous organization enlisted personnel of the division were exclusively Philippine Scouts. The War Department also proposed organizing a second Philippine Scout division, the [[14th Infantry Division (United States)|14th]], but never did so.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alexander M. Bielakowski Ph.D.|title=Ethnic and Racial Minorities in the U.S. Military: An Encyclopedia &#91;2 volumes&#93;|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w_Mqj6UuRgQC&pg=PT157|date=11 January 2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-428-3|pages=157\u2013}}</ref> In the end [[Harry S. Truman|President Truman]] disbanded the Philippine Scouts as an official element of the United States Army, and all of their unit colors were retired in 1947,<ref>{{cite book |title=MANEUVER AND FIREPOWER |last=Wilson |first=John B. |author2=Jeffrey J. Clarke |year=1998 |publisher=[[Center of Military History]], [[United States Army]] |location=Washington D.C. |page=212 |url=http://www.history.army.mil/catalog/pubs/60/60-14.html|chapter=Chapter VIII: An Interlude of Peace|chapterurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027171421/http://www.history.army.mil/books/Lineage/M-F/chapter8.htm |accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and finally disbanded in December 1948.<ref>{{cite book |title=World War 2 Pacific island guide |last=Rottman |first=Godron L. |year=2002 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |location=Westport, Connecticut |isbn=978-0-313-31395-0 |page=318 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ChyilRml0hcC&lpg=PA318&dq=guerrilla%20Philippine%20liberation%20fighting%20Japanese&pg=PA318#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nMany of the former Philippine Scouts went on to serve the United States in military careers of twenty and more years, campaigning in the [[Korean War]], the build-up to the planned invasion of Cuba during the October 1962 Missile Crisis, the [[Vietnam War]], and the Cold War. Children of the Scouts (known as \"Army Soup\" in pre-World War II Fort William McKinley days) sometimes carried on their fathers' military traditions and also became US Army soldiers and Marines. Two Philippine Scout children even earned the stars of US Army generals: Lt. General [[Edward Soriano]] and Major General [[Antonio M. Taguba]]. A third, Brig. General [[Oscar Hilman]], a native of Washington state and an armor officer who had started out as an enlisted man, earned his star in a long career in the Army National Guard.\n\nUnlike other non-citizen veterans, veterans of the Philippine Division and other Filipinos who fought as part of the [[USAFFE]] were never granted citizenship. Since 1993, various bills have been introduced to the [[United States Congress]] under the name [[Filipino Veterans Fairness Act]] to rectify this. However, this was a complicated matter as after the liberation of the Philippines members of the Philippine Scouts were offered enlistments and in some applicable cases commissions in the US Army and subsequent citizenship. Large numbers of \"old\" Philippine Scouts (those enlisting before or during World War II) took advantage of this. However, most \"new\" Philippine Scouts (those recruited following the war, mostly for occupation duty on Okinawa and elsewhere) were not offered citizenship. Language similar to the aforementioned proposed legislation was inserted by the Senate into the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]]<ref>{{cite news |first=Rick|last=Maze |title=Senate puts Filipino vet pensions in stimulus |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2009/01/military_filipinoscouts_stimulus_012909w/ |format=News article |work=Army Times |date=2008-01-29|accessdate=2009-01-30 |quote=Buried inside the Senate bill, which includes tax cuts and new spending initiatives intended to create jobs in the U.S., the Filipino payment was inserted at the urging of Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, the new chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee and a longtime supporter of monthly pensions for World War II Filipino veterans.}}</ref> which was signed into law. This provided a one-time payment to those veterans who are recognized as being soldiers or recognized guerrilla members by the United States or their surviving spouse. Even this, however, falls far short of the benefits available to similar veterans of other units.\n\nIn 2012, a [[documentary film]] named ''Forgotten Soldiers'' was produced by Donald A. Pata, with the help of Associate Instructor Chris Schaefer of the [[University of Utah]], and narrated by [[Lou Diamond Phillips]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Forgotten Soldiers: A Film Recognizing the Bravery and Courage of WWII's Philippine Scouts |author=Malou Liwanag-Bledsoe |url=http://www.asianjournal.com/aj-magazine/something-filipino/17559-forgotten-soldiers-a-film-recognizing-the-bravery-and-courage-of-wwiis-philippine-scouts.html |newspaper=Asian Journal |date=3 October 2012 |accessdate=5 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128075437/http://asianjournal.com/aj-magazine/something-filipino/17559-forgotten-soldiers-a-film-recognizing-the-bravery-and-courage-of-wwiis-philippine-scouts.html |archivedate=28 January 2013 }}</ref> The film received awards from the City of [[Los Angeles]], the [[California Senate]], [[County of Los Angeles]], and at the [[Beloit International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news |title=City of LA recognizes Donald Plata for 'Forgotten' Soldiers |url=http://www.asianjournal.com/community/community-news/17827-city-of-la-recognizes-donald-plata-for-forgotten-soldiers-.html |newspaper=Asian Journal |date=19 October 2012 |accessdate=5 May 2013 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Philippine Scouts==\n* [[Vicente Barros]] \u2013 Major, U.S. Army, the only Filipino officer among the ranks of Americans during the formation of the [[Philippine National Guard]] in 1917.<ref>{{cite news |title=THE CORNERSTONE OF PHILIPPINE INDEPENDENCE: A Narrative Of Seven Years |author=Francis Burton Harrison |url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/AFJ2343.0001.001/192 |pages=166 |publisher=Kessinger Publishing, LLC |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=17 April 2014}}<br />{{cite book|author=Francis Burton Harrison|title=The Corner-stone of Philippine Independence|url=https://archive.org/details/cornerstonephil00harrgoog|year=1922|publisher=Century Company|page=[https://archive.org/details/cornerstonephil00harrgoog/page/n196 166]}}</ref> Became advisor to the Philippine Commonwealth militia, the National Volunteers of the Philippines in 1935.<ref>{{cite news |title=THE PHILIPPINE ARMY, 1935-1942 |author=Ricardo Trota Jose |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kGocnp15GQ8C&pg=PA13&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=4#v=onepage&q=barros&f=false |pages=21 |publisher=Ateneo de Manila University Press (1992) |accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Willibald C. Bianchi]] \u2013 [[First Lieutenant#United States|First Lieutenant]], [[United States Army|U.S. Army]]. [[Medal of Honor]] recipient, 45th Infantry Regiment\n* [[Jose Calugas]] \u2013 [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]], U.S. Army. Medal of Honor recipient, 88th Field Artillery Regiment\n* [[Eddie Garcia]] \u2013 unknown rank, unknown unit. Actor, previously a Philippine Scout in Okinawa.<ref>{{cite news |last=Layug |first=Margaret Claire |date=22 June 2019 |title=Eddie Garcia honored by Philippine Army in memorial service |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/698592/eddie-garcia-honored-by-philippine-army-in-memorial-service/story/ |work=GMA News |location=Philippines |access-date=3 July 2019 }}</ref>\n* [[Louis C. Mosher]] \u2013 First Lieutenant, U.S. Army. Medal of Honor recipient\n* [[Alexander R. Nininger]] \u2013 [[Second Lieutenant#United States|Second Lieutenant]], U.S. Army. First Medal of Honor recipient in World War II, 57th Infantry Regiment\n* [[Jos\u00e9 B. N\u00edsperos]] \u2013 [[Private First Class#United States|Private First Class]], U.S. Army. First Asian Medal of Honor recipient, 34th Company\n* [[Juan Pajota]] \u2013 Captain, U.S. Army, 45th Infantry Regiment\n* [[Edwin Ramsey]] \u2013 First Lieutenant, U.S. Army. Led last horse cavalry charge in U.S. military history, 26th Cavalry Regiment\n* [[Benigno G. Tabora]] \u2013 [[Sergeant major#United States Army|Sergeant Major]], U.S. Army. [[Purple Heart]] recipient\n* [[Miguel White]] \u2013 Lieutenant, [[Philippine Commonwealth Army|Philippine Army]]. Olympian, previously a Philippine Scout.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mariano Villarin|title=We Remember Bataan and Corregidor: The Story of the American & Filipino Defenders of Bataan and Corregidor and Their Captivity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wj4gAAAAMAAJ|year=1990|publisher=Gateway Press|isbn=978-0-9626127-0-1|page=53}}</ref>\n* [[Teofilo Yldefonso]] \u2013 Sergeant, U.S. Army. Olympian, [[57th Infantry Regiment (United States)|57th Infantry Regiment]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Viloria |first=Barry |date= 8 September 2016 |title=What makes the first Filipino Olympics medalist a \u2018hero\u2019 |url=https://sports.abs-cbn.com/sportslifestyle/news/2016/09/08/what-makes-first-filipino-olympics-medalist-hero-15317 |work=ABS-CBN |location=Philippines |access-date=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alamo Scouts]]\n* [[Apache Scouts]]\n* [[Eskimo Scouts]]\n* [[Military history of Asian Americans]]\n* [[Military History of the Philippines]]\n* [[Military History of the United States]]\n* [[Navajo Scouts]]\n* [[Philippine Scout Mutiny]]\n* [[United States Army Indian Scouts]]\n\n==Bibliography and references==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Braden|first=Charles|editor=Wirt Robinson|title=Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U.S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y.: from its establishment, in 1802, to 1890, with the early history of the United States Military Academy |year=1920 |publisher=Houghton, Mifflin |location=University of Michigan |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SSHcAAAAMAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Coffman|first=Edward M.|title=Batson of the Philippine Scouts|year=1977|volume=VII|issue=3|journal=Journal of the US Army War College|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Rodao Garc\u00eda|author-link1=Florentino Rodao|first1=Florentino |last2=Rodr\u00edguez|first2=Felice Noelle |title=The Philippine Revolution of 1896: Ordinary Lives in Extraordinary Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l533SkJ2VCkC|year=2001|publisher=Ateneo de Manila University Press|isbn=978-971-550-386-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Knox|first=Donald |title=Death March: The Survivors of Bataan|url=https://archive.org/details/deathmarchsurviv00knox|url-access=registration|year=1981|publisher=Harcourt Brace Jovanovich|isbn=978-0-15-124094-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Linn|first=Brian McAllister |authorlink=Brian McAllister Linn|title=Guardians of Empire: The U.S. Army and the Pacific, 1902-1940|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zEOtgqPEkgwC|year=1999|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=978-0-8078-4815-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Morton|first=|title=The Fall of the Philippines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1AJgPwAACAAJ|year=2004|publisher=University Press of the Pacific|isbn=978-1-4102-1696-0}}\n* {{cite book|author=Philippine Scouts Heritage Society|title=The Philippine Scouts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Def9NwAACAAJ|year=1996|publisher=The Society}}\n* {{cite book|last=Olson|first=John E. |title=O'Donnell, Andersonville of the Pacific|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XaOEAAAAIAAJ|year=1985|publisher=J.E. Olson}}\n* {{cite book|author=United States War Dept|title=Annual Reports of the Secretary of War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QjhKQgAACAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Books LLC|isbn=978-1-4588-1628-3}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Philippine Scouts}}\n* [http://www.philippine-scouts.org/ Philippine Scouts Heritage Society]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110624063024/http://www.army.mil/asianpacificsoldiers/history/phillipineScouts.html Philippine Scouts on United States Army website]\n\n[[Category:Military history of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:20th-century military history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Philippines during World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Army in World War II]]\n[[Category:Philippine\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:Filipino-American history]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:United States military in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:History of the Philippines (1898\u20131946)]]\n", "name_user": "Juanmakabulos", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMacabebe Scouts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippine_Scouts"}
{"title_page": "White Furniture Company", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox NRHP | name =White Furniture Company\n  | nrhp_type =\n  | image =\n  | caption =\n  | location = E. Center and N. 5th Sts., [[Mebane, North Carolina]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|36|5|45|N|79|16|0|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = North Carolina#USA\n  | area =\n  | built =1905\n  | architect=\n  | architecture=\n  | added = July 29, 1982\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum=82003422\n<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n'''White Furniture Company''', was a major American producer of hand-crafted fine furniture for over a century (1881\u20131993). Founded by the White Brothers of [[Mebane, North Carolina]], the factory notably produced furnishings for the US government and the [[Grove Park Inn]].<ref name = nrhpinv>{{Cite web | author = Linda Marquez-Frees and Jim Sumner| title =White Furniture Company| work = National Register of Historic Places - Nomination and Inventory | date = March 1982| url = https://files.nc.gov/ncdcr/nr/AM0466.pdf | format = pdf | publisher = North Carolina State Historic Preservation Office | accessdate = 2014-08-01}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\n\nIn 1881, brothers Dave and Will White founded White Furniture Company.<ref name=\":0\">[http://uncpress.unc.edu/nc_encyclopedia/furniture.html Encyclopedia of North Carolina :: UNC Press<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  They used a small loan and $275 from working as telegraph operators as capital.<ref name=\":0\" /> Their father, Stephen A. White III, had acquired an amount of debt which soiled the family's name. Dave and Will pledged to repay their father's creditors, and such was the catalyst behind starting the factory.\n\nWill White served as president of the company and Dave White as general manager. \"The White Brothers were aggressive businessmen who took seriously their place in the town, and who, like many in the New South, equated industrial growth with civic duty and regional pride.\"\n\nWorking with only a [[Plane (tool)|plane]] and a [[boiler]], the initial manufacturing was limited to only round oak dining tables and wagon wheels. While reaching an early success in 1886, a local businessman invested funds to expand White Furniture and purchase more advanced machinery. Within a brief time, the company employed 32 people and manufactured tables, chairs, and a bedroom set. The solid-oak bedroom set sold for nine dollars and included a bed, dresser, and washstand.\n\n==Early history==\n\n=== The Panama Canal contracts===\n\nIn 1906, under the command of Chief Engineer [[John Frank Stevens]], hundreds of new building were built in Panama. These buildings were created to house army engineers and canal workers constructing the [[Panama Canal]]. The US government was in need of furniture for both enlisted men and American officers in Panama, and the bulk of the contracts was awarded to White's. A local newspaper reported, \"The first installment of furniture for the Panama Canal, contracted for the government with the White Furniture Company. This train of cars was handsomely placarded, each car bearing a 20-foot banner worded 'FROM THE WHITE FURNITURE CO., MEBANE, N.C., FOR U.S. GOVERNMENT, PANAMA CANAL,' and then the company trademark, 'The White Line Guarantees Satisfaction.'\"\n\nThis was the first time a government contract of this type had been awarded to a 'southern factory'. A total of 58 boxcars was whipped from North Carolina to the Panama Canal.\n\nJust one year after being awarded the Panama contracts, in 1907, White Furniture Company was awarded \"Best manufacturer of American furniture\" at the Jamestown Exhibition. (A World's Fair celebration during the 300th anniversary of the founding of the [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown Settlement]].)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in North Carolina}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Industrial buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Industrial buildings completed in 1905]]\n[[Category:Furniture companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct furniture manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Alamance County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Alamance County, North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox NRHP | name =White Furniture Company\n  | nrhp_type =\n  | image =\n  | caption =\n  | location = E. Center and N. 5th Sts., [[Mebane, North Carolina]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|36|5|45|N|79|16|0|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = North Carolina#USA\n  | area =\n  | built =1905\n  | architect=\n  | architecture=\n  | added = July 29, 1982\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum=82003422\n<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n'''White Furniture Company''', was a major American producer of hand-crafted fine furniture for over a century (1881\u20131993). Founded by the White Brothers of [[Mebane, North Carolina]], the factory notably produced furnishings for the US government and the [[Grove Park Inn]].<ref name = nrhpinv>{{Cite web | author = Linda Marquez-Frees and Jim Sumner| title =White Furniture Company| work = National Register of Historic Places - Nomination and Inventory | date = March 1982| url = https://files.nc.gov/ncdcr/nr/AM0466.pdf | format = pdf | publisher = North Carolina State Historic Preservation Office | accessdate = 2014-08-01}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\n\nIn 1881, brothers Dave and Will White founded White Furniture Company.<ref name=\":0\">[http://uncpress.unc.edu/nc_encyclopedia/furniture.html Encyclopedia of North Carolina :: UNC Press<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  They used a small loan and $275 from working as telegraph operators as capital.<ref name=\":0\" /> Their father, Stephen A. White III, had acquired an amount of debt which soiled the family's name. Dave and Will pledged to repay their father's creditors, and such was the catalyst behind starting the factory.\n\nWill White served as president of the company and Dave White as general manager. \"The White Brothers were aggressive businessmen who took seriously their place in the town, and who, like many in the New South, equated industrial growth with civic duty and regional pride.\"\n\nWorking with only a [[Plane (tool)|plane]] and a [[boiler]], the initial manufacturing was limited to only round oak dining tables and wagon wheels. While reaching an early success in 1886, a local businessman invested funds to expand White Furniture and purchase more advanced machinery. Within a brief time, the company employed 32 people and manufactured tables, chairs, and a bedroom set. The solid-oak bedroom set sold for nine dollars and included a bed, dresser, and washstand.\n\n==Early history==\n\n=== The Panama Canal contracts===\n\nIn 1906, under the command of Chief Engineer John Frank Stevens, hundreds of new building were built in Panama. These buildings were created to house army engineers and canal workers constructing the [[Panama Canal]]. The US government was in need of furniture for both enlisted men and American officers in Panama, and the bulk of the contracts was awarded to White's. A local newspaper reported, \"The first installment of furniture for the Panama Canal, contracted for the government with the White Furniture Company. This train of cars was handsomely placarded, each car bearing a 20-foot banner worded 'FROM THE WHITE FURNITURE CO., MEBANE, N.C., FOR U.S. GOVERNMENT, PANAMA CANAL,' and then the company trademark, 'The White Line Guarantees Satisfaction.'\"\n\nThis was the first time a government contract of this type had been awarded to a 'southern factory'. A total of 58 boxcars was whipped from North Carolina to the Panama Canal.\n\nJust one year after being awarded the Panama contracts, in 1907, White Furniture Company was awarded \"Best manufacturer of American furniture\" at the Jamestown Exhibition. (A World's Fair celebration during the 300th anniversary of the founding of the [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown Settlement]].)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in North Carolina}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Industrial buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Industrial buildings completed in 1905]]\n[[Category:Furniture companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct furniture manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Alamance County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Alamance County, North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Leahsch", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Panama Canal contracts:added a wikilink to John Frank Stevens in order to give more background information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_Furniture_Company"}
{"title_page": "Liam Payne", "text_new": "{{short description|English singer and songwriter}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Liam Payne\n| image              = Liam Payne in October 2018.jpg\n| caption            = Payne in 2018\n| birth_name         = Liam James Payne\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1993|8|29}}<ref>{{cite web|title=One Direction Star Liam Payne Celebrates 21st Birthday in Chicago|url=http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2014/08/29/one-direction-liam-payne-chicago-birthday-tour/|publisher=Chicago.cbslocal.com|accessdate=20 October 2015|date=29 August 2014}}</ref>\n| other_names        = \n| birth_place        = [[Wolverhampton]], England\n| net_worth          = \u00a342&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/richest-young-musicians-in-britain-2018-sunday-times-rich-list-2018-5/#4-niall-horan-one-direction-46-million-8|title=The 11 richest young musicians in Britain|last=Dodgson|first=Lindsay|work=Business Insider UK|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n| years_active       = 2008\u2013present\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}}\n| partner            = [[Cheryl (singer)|Cheryl]] (2016\u20132018)\n| children           = 1\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist |embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              =  {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| instrument         = Vocals<!--- For instrument(s) the artist is primarily notable for using, per reliable sources. The instruments infobox parameter is not intended as a WP:COATRACK for every instrument the subject has ever used; see: [[Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument]]-->\n| label              = {{hlist|[[Syco Music|Syco]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]|[[Republic Records|Republic]]}}\n| associated_acts    = {{hlist| Leon Hlabathi [https://instagram.com/leonhlabathi] | [[One Direction]]|[[Quavo]]|[[Zedd]]|[[J Balvin]]|[[Jonas Blue]]|[[Lennon Stella]]|[[A Boogie wit da Hoodie]]}}\n| website            = {{URL|liampayneofficial.com}}}}\n}}\n\n'''Liam James Payne''' (born 29 August 1993) is an English singer and songwriter. He rose to fame as a member of the boy band [[One Direction]]. Payne made his debut as a singer when he auditioned for the British television series ''[[The X Factor]]'' in 2008. After being eliminated as a solo performer, he auditioned again in 2010 and was put into a group with four other contestants to form One Direction.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Oliver|first1=Sarah|title=Zayn Malik and Liam Payne \u2013 The Biography|date=2014|publisher=John Blake Publishing|location=New York|isbn=978-1782199496}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Nash|first1=Victoria|title=Liam Payne now sprinting to X Factor success|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/entertainment/2010/09/11/liam-payne-now-sprinting-to-x-factor-success/|website=Express and Star|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> The group has since released five albums, embarked on four world tours, and won [[List of awards and nominations received by One Direction|several awards]]. Payne has worked with other producers under the monikers \"Big Payno\" and \"Payno\" creating remixes for songs by his group and [[Cheryl (entertainer)|Cheryl]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/one-direction/news/listen-to-1ds-liam-payno-payne-remix-of-cheryls-i-dont-care | title=Listen to 1D's Liam Payne's Remix of Cheryl's new single 'I Don't Care'. | work=MTV UK | date=14 October 2014 | accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Payne signed a recording deal with [[Republic Records]] in North America.<ref name=\"republic\">{{cite web |last1=Kaufman |first1=Gil |title=Liam Payne Joins Ariana Grande & the Weeknd on Republic Records Roster |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7542073/liam-payne-signs-to-republic-records-joins-ariana-grande-the-weeknd- |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=16 August 2018 |date=17 October 2016}}</ref> In May 2017, Payne released \"[[Strip That Down]]\" as the lead single from his upcoming debut album. It peaked at number three on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and number ten on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], being certified platinum in both countries. His debut album, ''[[LP1 (Liam Payne album)|LP1]]'', was released on 6 December 2019.\n\n==Early life==\nPayne was born in [[Wolverhampton]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], England. He is the son of Karen, an infant nurse, and Geoff Payne, a fitter. He has two older sisters, Nicola and Ruth Payne.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mums of One Direction stars reveal how the boys have grown into music sensations|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/celebrity/mums-of-one-direction-stars-reveal-1119384|accessdate=17 July 2015|agency=Daily Record|publisher=Trinity Mirror|date=16 April 2012}}</ref> Payne was born three weeks early, getting ill frequently. Until the age of four, Payne had regular tests done in hospital as doctors noticed one of his kidneys was scarred and dysfunctional. To help cope with the pain, he had sixteen injections in his arm every morning and another sixteen every evening as a child.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davies|first1=Rebecca|title=One Direction's Liam Payne: 'I effectively died as a baby' |agency=Digital Spy|date=18 September 2011}}</ref> As a student, Payne was heavily involved in sports, particularly cross country running. Payne originally joined the Wolverhampton and Bilston Athletics Club to pursue his running career. Payne claimed in an interview that he was '3rd best in the country at one point'. <ref>{{cite web|author=LaureusVerified account |url=https://twitter.com/LaureusSport/status/1229459812737527808 |title=Laureus on Twitter: \"\"I was the third best in the country at one point.\" @LiamPayne the Olympian? \u0111&#x;\u02dc\u017b #Laureus20 \u0111&#x;\u017d\u013d Laureus Live:  |website=Twitter.com |date=2020-02-17 |accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>[https://www.thepowerof10.info/athletes/profile.aspx?athleteid=59036] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs he was dealing with bullying from some older students in secondary school, he took up boxing lessons at the age of twelve.<ref>{{cite news|title=One Direction's Liam Payne: \"I Was Devastated After Breaking Up With Danielle Peazer|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/one-direction/news/liam-payne-danielle-peazer-break-up/|agency=Capital FM}}</ref> Payne completed 11 [[GCSE]]s at St Peter's Collegiate School before moving on to study music technology at Wolverhampton College's Paget Road campus.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nPayne was first introduced to the world of show business at age twelve as a member of the Pink Productions Theatre Company, even appearing as Tony Manero from ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Liam Payne theatre company holds auditions to find their 'next star'|url=http://nativemonster.com/lifestyle/liam-payne-theatre-company-on-look-out-for-next-star|publisher=Nativemonster.com|accessdate=20 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222120410/http://nativemonster.com/lifestyle/liam-payne-theatre-company-on-look-out-for-next-star|archive-date=22 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Payne had previously performed in front of a crowd of 26,000 during a [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] football match.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Liam Payne's journey from Bushbury to Big Apple|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/entertainment/music/2012/03/17/liam-paynes-journey-from-bushbury-to-big-apple/|publisher=Expressandstar.com|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2008\u20132015: ''The X-Factor'' and One Direction===\nPayne first auditioned for the  [[The X Factor (UK series 5)|fifth series]] of the British Singing Competition ''[[The X Factor (UK)|The X Factor]]'' in 2008, at just 14 years old. Payne moved past the first round after performing [[Frank Sinatra]]'s \"Fly Me to the Moon\". He was subsequently cut at the Boot Camp stage, but [[Simon Cowell]], who then changed his mind and asked Payne to return for the judges' houses stage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/entertainment/2010/09/06/liam-payne-shows-he-has-the-x-factor/|title=Liam Payne shows he has the X Factor|newspaper=Wolverhampton Express And Star|date=6 September 2010|accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref> Payne was cut again during judges' houses, but was encouraged by Cowell to \"come back in two years\".<ref>{{cite episode\n| title      = Episode 1\n| series     = The X Factor (series 5)\n| serieslink = The X Factor (UK)\n| station    = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| location   = London\n| airdate    = 16 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nPayne returned to the show in 2010 for the [[The X Factor (UK series 7)|seventh series]]. He auditioned with the [[Michael Bubl\u00e9]] version of \"[[Cry Me a River (1953 song)|Cry Me a River]]\", which earned him four yeses and a standing ovation from Cowell. Payne was considered the second favourite to win the competition following his solo audition.<ref>{{cite episode\n| title      = Episode 3\n| series     = The X Factor (series 7)\n| serieslink = The X Factor (UK)\n| station    = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| location       = London\n| airdate    = 4 September 2010\n}}</ref> He failed to progress to the \"Boys\" category at judges' houses, but after a suggestion by [[Simon Cowell]], Payne, along with [[Harry Styles]], [[Niall Horan]], [[Louis Tomlinson]], and [[Zayn Malik]], were put together to form a five-piece boy band at [[Wembley Arena]], during the bootcamp stage of the competition, thus qualifying for the \"Groups\" category.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kelly |first=Kristy |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a331792/nicole-scherzinger-i-did-simon-cowell-a-favor-with-one-direction.html#~piG1xvJl9hf7cy |title=Nicole Scherzinger: 'I did Simon Cowell a favour with One Direction' |work=Digital Spy |date=26 July 2011 |accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> Subsequently, the group got together for two weeks to get to know each other and to practice. For their qualifying song at Judges' houses, and their first song as a group, they performed an acoustic version of \"[[Torn (Ednaswap song)|Torn]]\". Simon Cowell later commented that the performance convinced him that the group \"were confident, fun, like a gang of friends, and kind of fearless as well.\" The group quickly gained popularity in the UK, ultimately coming in third place on the show.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exclusive Q&A: Simon Cowell on One Direction's Rise to Stardom|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/exclusive-q-a-simon-cowell-on-one-directions-rise-to-stardom-20120409|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=20 October 2015|date=2012-04-09}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Liam Payne Sydney Australia.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Liam Payne in 2012]]\nFollowing ''The X Factor'', [[One Direction]] were signed to Simon Cowell's Syco Entertainment in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nicholson|first1=Rebecca|title=Also-rans to world's biggest boy band: the rise of One Direction|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/17/one-direction-biggest-band-world|agency=The Guardian|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> A book licensed by One Direction, ''One Direction: Forever Young (Our Official X Factor Story)'', was released in February 2011 and topped ''[[The Sunday Times]]''' Best Seller list. Their debut single, \"[[What Makes You Beautiful]]\", was released in September 2011, and was a commercial and international success, reaching number one in several countries.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7408939/ask-billboard-one-directions-career-sales |title = Ask Billboard: One Direction's Career Sales}}</ref> Their debut album, ''[[Up All Night (One Direction album)|Up All Night]]'', was released in Ireland and the UK of November of that same year, charting at number one and number two, respectively. The album was released worldwide in March 2012, and One Direction became the first [[United Kingdom|UK]] group to have their debut album reach number one in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.idolator.com/6226811/one-direction-debut-chart-history?safari=1&Exc_D_LessThanPoint002_p1=1 | title=One Direction Debut at #1, Make Album Chart History| date=2012-03-21}}</ref> Following the release of the album, the group headlined the [[Up All Night Tour]]. Originally intended with shows taking place only in the UK and Ireland,<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1333935670URKQOKXYQQ?url=http://www.stereoboard.com/content/view/167954/9 | archivedate=9 April 2012 |url=http://www.stereoboard.com/content/view/167954/9 | title=One Direction Announce UK Tour Dates & Ticket Details - Stereoboard}}</ref> [[Australia]]n and [[North America]]n legs of the tour were added due to demand.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.idolator.com/6226892/one-direction-north-american-tour-dates?safari=1 |title = One Direction Reveal North American Tour Dates|date = 2012-03-21}}</ref> A commercial success, tickets for the tour sold out in minutes and garnered positive reviews from critics who applauded the band's singing abilities and stage presence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=HSWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.heraldsun.com.au%2Fentertainment%2Fone-direction-infection-sweeps-melbourne%2Fnews-story%2Fd24bd97352b8eb096d0a8ddf59405a03&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=114e1396fff7ed6a2acbb008e50de654-1575638693|title=Heraldsun.com.au &#124; Subscribe to the Herald Sun for exclusive stories|website=Heraldsun.com.au}}</ref> The band released ''[[Up All Night: The Live Tour]]'', a video album documenting the tour, in May 2012. That same month, One Direction's first book to be licensed in America, ''Dare to Dream: Life as One Direction'', was published and topped [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-06-10/paperback-books/list.html |work=The New York Times | title=Best Sellers | date=10 June 2012 | accessdate = 24 August 2012 | first=Gregory | last=Cowles}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, \"[[Live While We're Young]]\", the lead single from the group's second album, was released, and was a global success. Another single, \"[[Little Things (One Direction song)|Little Things]]\", spawned the band's second [[List of UK Singles Chart number ones of the 2010s|number one single]] in the UK.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/one-direction-score-number-1-single-and-album-__2564/ | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830142315/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/one-direction-score-number-1-single-and-album-__2564/ | archivedate=2018-08-30 |title = One Direction score Number 1 single AND album!}}</ref> In November 2012, the group released their second album, ''[[Take Me Home (One Direction album)|Take Me Home]]'', and it reached number one in over 35 countries. Reaching number one on the ''[[Billboard 200]]'', the group became the first boy band in US chart history to record two number-one albums in the same calendar year alongside becoming the first group since 2008 to record two number-one albums in the same year.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474059/one-directions-take-me-home-debuts-at-no-1-with-years-third-biggest-opening |title = One Direction's 'Take Me Home' Debuts at No. 1 with Year's Third-Biggest Opening}}</ref> Following the release of the album, the group embarked on their second headlining concert tour, the [[Take Me Home Tour (One Direction)|Take Me Home Tour]]. Performing 123 shows in North America, Asia, Oceania, and Europe, grossing $114 million. During the tour, One Direction covered [[Wheatus]]'s \"Teenage Dirtbag\". In the original song lead vocalist [[Brendan Brown]] performs a segment in a \"female voice\" which, in One Direction's rendition of the song Payne covered in falsetto. This garnered praise from Brown, who commented, \"You can do my girl part anytime.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=One Direction Get 'Teenage Dirtbag' Love|url=http://www.mstarz.com/articles/15598/20130702/one-direction-teenage-dirtbag-love-photo-video-wheatus-praises-louis.htm|publisher=Mstarz.com|accessdate=20 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208073827/http://www.mstarz.com/articles/15598/20130702/one-direction-teenage-dirtbag-love-photo-video-wheatus-praises-louis.htm|archive-date=8 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2013, ''[[One Direction: This Is Us]]'', a [[3D film|3-D]] [[documentary]] [[concert film]] was released, accumalting a box office gross of $68.5 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/aug/20/one-direction-fans-film-premiere|title=One Direction fans queue for prime view of a global success story|first=Caroline|last=Sullivan|date=20 August 2013|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> One Direction's third book, ''One Direction: Where We Are: Our Band, Our Story: 100% Official'', was released that same month.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/one-direction-announces-we-are-556785 |title = One Direction Announces 'Where We Are' Book|website=Hollywoodreporter.com}}</ref>\n\nThe group's third album, ''[[Midnight Memories]]'', was released in November of that same year. It was the best-selling album worldwide in 2013 with 4 million copies sold globally.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28599903 | title=One Direction top global album chart| work=BBC News| date=August 2014}}</ref> The album's lead single, [[Best Song Ever]], is their highest charting single in the US to date.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/music/One-Direction/chart-history/hot-100 |title = One Direction Chart History|website=Billboard.com}}</ref> The group embarked on their third headling tour, the [[Where We Are Tour (One Direction)|Where We Are Tour]]. Tickets sold out in minutes,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/one-direction/news/one-direction-tour-tickets-sell-out-in-minutes |title = One Direction Tour Tickets Sell Out in Minutes |website=Mtv.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://metro.co.uk/2013/05/25/fans-left-devastated-as-one-direction-where-we-are-tour-tickets-sell-out-in-minutes-3808314/ | title=1D add tour dates after 'instant sell-out'|website=Metro.co.uk| date=2013-05-25}}</ref> and more shows were added due to \"overwhelming demand.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/2013/12/4/18541298/one-direction-adds-show-to-chicago-stop-on-tour |title = One Direction adds show to Chicago stop on tour|date = 2013-12-04}}</ref> The tour was their first all-stadium tour, averaging 49,848 fans per show.<ref name=\"billboard1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6281518/one-direction-where-we-are-tour-three-million | title=One Direction's Where We Are Tour Attended by 3.4 Million Fans|website=Billboard.com}}</ref> In total, the tour grossed over $290 million and was the highest-grossing tour of 2014, the 15th [[List of highest-grossing concert tours|highest-grossing concert tour]] of all time, and is still the highest-grossing tour of all time by a vocal group.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2015/03/24/these-were-the-10-highest-grossing-tours-of-2014/#673c117c3643 |title = These Were the 10 Highest-Grossing Tours of 2014|website=Forbes.com}}</ref> The tour was attended by 3.4 million fans.<ref name=\"billboard1\"/> In September 2014, One Direction's fourth book, ''One Direction: Who We Are: Our Official Autobiography'' was released. The group's second [[concert film]], ''[[One Direction: Where We Are \u2013 The Concert Film]]'', was released in October 2014, showing footage of the band's shows at [[San Siro Stadium]] in [[Milan, Italy]]. In November 2014, the group's fourth album, ''[[Four (One Direction album)|Four]]'', was released, making it the last album to include [[Zayn Malik]]. Singles \"[[Steal My Girl]]\" and \"[[Night Changes]]\" were released, both achieving platinum status in the US among other countries.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=One+Direction&ti=Steal+My+Girl#search_section |title = Gold & Platinum|website=Riaa.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=One+Direction&ti=Night+Changes#search_section |title = Gold & Platinum|website=Riaa.com}}</ref> The album debuted number one in 18 countries, selling 3.2 million copies.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lthqofficial.com/news/2018/11/17/fourth-anniversary-of-one-directions-album-four |title = Fourth Anniversary of One Direction's Album, Four \u2014 LTHQ Official}}</ref> One Direction became the only group in the 58-year history of the [[Billboard Hot 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart to have their first four albums debut at number one.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Caufield|first1=Keith|title=One Direction's 'Four' Makes Historic No. 1 Debut on Billboard 200 Chart|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6327789/one-direction-four-no-1-debut-billboard-200|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> The group embarked on their fourth headlining world tour, the [[On the Road Again Tour]], grossing $208 million and selling 2.3 million tickets. In November 2015, One Direction's fifth album, ''[[Made in the A.M.]]'', was released. Singles \"[[Drag Me Down]]\" and \"[[Perfect (One Direction song)|Perfect]]\" both debuted at number one in various countries, and the album reached number one in the UK and number two on the US ''Billboard 200''. Following the release of the album, the group went on an indefinite hiatus.\n\nFollowing the departure of former member [[Zayn Malik]], Payne was tasked with taking over the bulk of Malik's vocals.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCorimck|first1=Neil|title=One Direction, Millennium Stadium Cardiff, review: 'business as usual'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/live-music-reviews/11655547/One-Direction-Millenium-Stadium-Cardiff-review-In-an-ear-battering-competition-between-a-giant-PA-and-female-fandom-Id-say-the-girls-just-about-edged-it.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> Bandmate [[Harry Styles]] admitted, \"Liam [Payne] stepped up to do the high notes. He kicks them in the bollocks every show. He doesn't hold back.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Harry Styles Talks Incredible Fans & Liam Payne Not Holding Back On Zayn Malik's Solos|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/harry-styles/news/harry-styles-talks-incredible-fans-liam-payne-not-holding-back-on-zayn-maliks-solos|agency=MTV|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nPayne was known as one of the principal songwriters in One Direction, credited for co-writing more than half of the songs on the band's third and fourth album.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Corner|first1=Lewis|title=One Direction's Liam Payne, Louis Tomlinson named band's top earners|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a555301/one-directions-liam-payne-louis-tomlinson-named-bands-top-earners.html#~piJh0d0x9CXVuD|publisher=Digitalspy.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Liam Payne Now Writing Post-Zayn 1D Songs|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2008232/liam-payne-now-writing-post-zayn-1d-songs-guess-next-album-title/|publisher=Inquisitr.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present: Solo projects and ''LP1''===\nPayne began working as a producer under the monikers \"Big Payno\" or \"Payno\", teaming up with fellow producers AfterHrs to remix several tracks including [[Cheryl Cole]]'s \"I Don't Care\" in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Villa|first1=Lucas|title=One Direction's Liam Payne remixes latest singles by his band and Cheryl|url=http://www.axs.com/listen-one-direction-s-liam-payne-remixes-latest-singles-by-his-band-a-24150|publisher=Axs.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> Some EDM websites noted Payne's remixes were venturing into [[future house]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sachs|first1=Elliot|title=One Direction Star Makes Surprisingly Good House Music|url=http://www.youredm.com/2014/10/17/one-direction-star-makes-surprisingly-good-house-music/|publisher=Youredm.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Villa|first1=Lucas|title=One Direction premiere Liam Payne's Big Payno remix of 'You & I'|url=http://www.axs.com/news/one-direction-premiere-liam-payne-s-big-payno-remix-of-you-i-16081}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=One Direction Pop Star is Producing Future House Music Now|url=http://edm.com/articles/2014-10-17/one-direction-liam-payne-producing-future-house|publisher=Edm.com|accessdate=20 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222171221/http://edm.com/articles/2014-10-17/one-direction-liam-payne-producing-future-house|archive-date=22 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Payne is also credited with writing Cole's \"I Won't Break\", off her album ''[[Only Human (Cheryl Cole album)|Only Human]]''.\n\nIn August 2014, Payne created and became director of Hampton Music Limited, a publishing company under which his solo projects will appear.<ref name=\"latinpost.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/111272/20160125/jennifer-lopez-liam-payne-working-on-new-music-together.htm|title=Jennifer Lopez, Liam Payne Working on New Music Together?|last1=Minnis|first1=Glenn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aihitdata.com/company/01701875/hampton-music-limited/overview|title=HAMPTON MUSIC LIMITED - Overview &#124; aiHit|first=Yurii|last=Biurher|website=Aihitdata.com}}</ref> Australian band [[5 Seconds of Summer]] is signed to One Mode Productions Limited, on which Payne serves as one of the directors.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6273836/one-direction-secret-investment-5-seconds-summer |title=Details on One Direction's Secret Financial Investment in 5 Seconds of Summer |website=Billboard.com}}</ref>\n\nPayne began working on future projects collaborating with [[Juicy J]] on seven tracks with more in the works,<ref>{{cite news|title=Juicy J is working with One Direction's Liam Payne|url=http://www.factmag.com/2015/01/30/juicy-j-is-working-with-one-directions-liam-payne/|agency=Fact Mag|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Juicy J made seven songs with Liam Payne: 'We are working on a lot of different things'|url=http://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/londonnewsdesk/view/121633/|publisher=Pressparty.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> [[DJ Mustard]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Liam Payne of One Direction worked with DJ Mustard on new material|url=http://www.dtgre.com/2015/02/liam-payne-of-one-direction-worked-with.html|publisher=Dtgre.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> and [[Miguel (singer)|Miguel]].<ref>{{cite news|title=One Direction's Liam Payne records 'dance' track with Miguel|url=http://www.nme.com/news/one-direction/72221|publisher=Nme.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> He has also been in the studio with producer and performing artist [[Pharrell Williams]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pharrell Williams And 1D's Liam Payne \"Looking Forward\" To Recording Studio Session|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/pharrell-williams/news/one-direction-liam-payne-new-music/#d2SIqPzIJsSgLcwf.97|publisher=Capitalfm.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> Payne also contacted [[The Collective (band)|The Collective]] member and YouTube musician and producer [[William Singe|Will Singe]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thomson|first1=Heather|title=LIiam Payne Contacts Music Producer -Already Working on a Solo Career?|url=http://www.m-magazine.com/posts/liam-payne-contacts-music-producer-already-working-on-a-solo-career-73149|publisher=M-magazine.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Payne collaborated with songwriter [[Jamie Scott]] on Irish band [[Hometown (band)|Hometown]]'s single \"The Night We Met\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goss.ie/2015/10/louis-walsh-reveals-liam-payne-wrote-hometowns-new-track/50007/|title=Louis Walsh reveals Liam Payne wrote Hometown's new track|last1=Martin|first1=Rachel|access-date=22 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151024211202/http://www.goss.ie/2015/10/louis-walsh-reveals-liam-payne-wrote-hometowns-new-track/50007/|archive-date=24 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In early 2016, Payne featured on a track titled \"You\" by [[Wiz Khalifa]] and [[Juicy J]]. Payne denied that the track was a single, but it was confirmed to be a leak from an untitled, unreleased mixtape.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bet.com/news/music/2016/04/20/boy-band-crooner-has-wiz-khalifa---juicy-j-to-thank-for-bringing.html|title=Wiz Khalifa and Juicy J Brought A Member Of One Direction Into The Hip Hop Game|last1=Orcutt|first1=KC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7340846/liam-payne-juicy-j-wiz-khalifa-leak-demo|title=Liam Payne Says 'Leaked' Juicy J & Wiz Khalifa Song Is Just a Demo: 'I Do Not Have a Single'|last1=Greenwald|first1=Morgan}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, it was announced that Payne had signed a recording contract with [[Republic Records]].<ref name=\"republic\"/> His debut solo single \"[[Strip That Down]]\", featuring [[Quavo]] and co-written with [[Ed Sheeran]] and [[Steve Mac]], was released on 19 May 2017,<ref name=\"firstsingle\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7792797/liam-payne-new-single-strip-that-down-release-date |title=Liam Payne Officially Announces First Solo Single, 'Strip That Down,' Featuring Quavo |date=11 May 2017 |website=Billboard.com |accessdate=11 May 2017}}</ref> and sent to US [[contemporary hit radio]] on 23 May.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases |title=Top 40/Mainstream > Future Releases |website=AllAccess.com |accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> Payne later released the single \"[[Bedroom Floor]]\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/4WwvVW7q1HNj4zxf1jtYBmX/14-things-we-discovered-about-liam-payne-on-the-radio-1-breakfast-show |title=14 things we discovered about Liam Payne on the Radio 1 Breakfast Show |date=19 May 2017 |work=BBC |accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> and the collaboration with [[Zedd]], \"[[Get Low (Zedd and Liam Payne song)|Get Low]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/liam-payne/news/zedd-collaboration-get-low/ |title=We Actually Can't Handle Liam Payne & Zedd's Dad Jokes In Their BTS Intagram Video |date=16 June 2017 |work=Capital FM |accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> Regarding his forthcoming debut album, Payne stated:\n\n{{quote|It's very eclectic. It's more like my playlist album; my favorite playlist of songs that I have made over the past year. So, some slow jams, there's a couple of dance songs on there, with some R&B stuff. So there's a lot \u2013 it's a lot of different stuff.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://933flz.iheart.com/content/2017-05-18-interview-liam-payne-talks-strip-that-down-teases-eclectic-upcoming-solo-album/ |title=INTERVIEW: Liam Payne Talks 'Strip That Down' & Teases 'Eclectic' Upcoming Solo Album |date=18 May 2017 |work=iHeartRadio |accessdate=27 May 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nIn January 2018, Payne and [[Rita Ora]] released the single \"[[For You (Liam Payne and Rita Ora song)|For You]]\" from the soundtrack of the film ''[[Fifty Shades Freed (film)|Fifty Shades Freed]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Jennifer|title=Rita Ora and Liam Payne's Fifty Shades Collab Will Be Your First Favorite Song of 2018|url=http://www.instyle.com/news/rita-ora-liam-payne-fifty-shades-freed-song-for-you|work=[[InStyle]]|date=3 January 2018|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref> In April 2018, Payne released \"[[Familiar (song)|Familiar]]\" with [[J Balvin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/liam-payne-to-release-new-single-familiar-featuring-j-balvin__21992/|title=Liam Payne is teaming up with J Balvin on his new single|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|last=White|first=Jack|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=27 February 2018}}</ref> He announced his debut album would be released on 14 September 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8456142/liam-payne-announces-album-release-date-interview-video|title=Liam Payne Reveals September Album Release Date, Hints at One Direction Reunion: Watch|website=Billboard.com|last=Weatherby|first=Taylor|date=15 May 2018|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2018, Payne performed in front of more than 100,000 people during a free concert at [[Global Village (Dubai)|Global Village 2018]] in Dubai.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/payne-performs-to-over-100k-in-dubai/|title=Payne performs to over 100k in Dubai|newspaper=[[Khaleej Times]]|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/music/liam-payne-to-play-free-gig-in-dubai-1.712268|title=Liam Payne to play free gig in Dubai|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|last=McFarlane|first=Nyree|date=12 March 2018|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> He released his first [[extended play]], ''[[First Time (EP)|First Time]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last=Muraro |first=Alberto |title=Liam Payne: l'EP First Time esce il 24 agosto! Ecco la lettera ai fan! |url=https://www.gingergeneration.it/n/liam-payne-first-time-ep-326076-n.htm |accessdate=17 August 2018 |work=Ginger Generation |date=16 August 2018 |language=Italian}}</ref> which features a collaboration with [[French Montana]] of the same name, on 24 August 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shenton |first=Zoe |title=Liam Payne reveals new track is out next week as he makes big changes to album after Cheryl split |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/liam-payne-reveals-new-track-13093823 |accessdate=17 August 2018 |work=Daily Mirror |date=17 August 2018}}</ref> Prior to the EP's release, Payne announced that he is putting off his album to make some adjustments to it.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2018/0819/986065-liam-payne-making-changes-to-album-due-august-24/|title=Liam Payne making changes to his debut album|website=RTE|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe contributed vocals on [[Jonas Blue]]'s song \"[[Polaroid (Jonas Blue, Liam Payne and Lennon Stella song)|Polaroid]]\", along with [[Lennon Stella]], released on 5 October 2018.\n\nPayne released the song \"[[Stack It Up]]\", featuring American rapper [[A Boogie wit da Hoodie]], on 18 September 2019. After its release, Payne revealed that his album is \"finished\" and would more likely released in 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/111770-liam-paynes-solo-album-wont-come-out-until-2020/|title=Liam Payne's solo album won't come out until 2020|website=[[The List (magazine)|The List]]|date=28 September 2019|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref> although in October, the album, ''[[LP1 (Liam Payne album)|LP1]]'', was confirmed for a 6 December 2019 release date. It peaked at number 17 in the UK and at number 111 in the US.\n\n==Artistry==\nLiam Payne is a [[Pop music|pop]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/liam-payne-review-lp1-album-tracklist-stream-cheryl-one-direction-a9233971.html|title=Liam Payne review \u2013 LP1: From One Direction to One Dimensional|publisher=[[Independent (newspaper)|Independent]]|last=Brown|first=Helen|date=6 December 2019|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref> and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/one-direction-22-1194241|title=Liam Payne turns R&B in teaser of post-One Direction solo track \u2013 listen|publisher=[[NME]]|last=Morgan Britton|first=Luke|date=16 January 2016|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref> singer who explores other genres like [[Electronic music|electronic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Liam Payne Bio, Albums, Streaming Links, Credits|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/liam-payne-mn0002854539|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe cites [[Pharrell Williams]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Liam Payne Says One Direction 'Will Work Together Again': See His 'Attitude' Cover|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6693050/liam-payne-attitude-cover-gay-uk-magazine-one-direction|publisher=Billboard.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> [[Justin Timberlake]],<ref>{{cite news|title=One Direction's Liam Payne On Bumping Into Justin Timberlake At The BRITs 2013|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/one-direction/news/liam-payne-justin-timberlake-brit-awards-2013/#3Ij2coJw0GRwWjhD.97|publisher=Capitalfm.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> and [[Usher (musician)|Usher]] as major musical influences.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://home.bt.com/news/showbiz-news/liam-payne-im-not-ready-to-make-statement-music-like-taylor-swift-11364208637515|title=Liam Payne: I'm not ready to make statement music like Taylor Swift|website=[[BT Consumer|BT]]|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c3oC5mM57Gg|title= Liam Payne \u2013 Liam Payne On \"Strip That Down\" and New Music| website=[[Vevo]]|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> \"The person who has inspired me most is Pharrell Williams who I worked with a while back. I got talking to his producer recently and asked him what Pharrell was like when he was younger, and he said to me that when he was my age he couldn\u2019t press a note on a keyboard. And that was amazing to me because at 22 I thought I was too old to learn guitar,\" revealed Payne.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Guiltenane|first1=Christian|title=Attitude Magazine|url=http://attitude.co.uk/tag/liam-payne/|publisher=Attitude.co.uk|issue=October 2015|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nAs a member on One Direction, Payne has also supported [[Comic Relief]],<ref>{{cite news|title=One Direction Raises Over \u00a32 Million For Red Nose Day 2013|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/10927-one-direction-raises-over-2-million-for-red-nose-day-2013|publisher=Looktothestars.org|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> and a new initiative titled Action 1D \"to help better the future\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sherman|first1=Maria|title=One Direction Launch Charity Initiative \"Action 1D\"|url=http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2015/07/one-direction-launch-charity-action-1d|publisher=Fuse.tv|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nPayne is an avid supporter of [[Unicef]] and teamed up with tennis star [[Andy Murray]], [[Jack Whitehall]] and [[Clare Balding]] in support of Unicef UK's Children in Danger Summer Disease Appeal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Andy Murray, Liam Payne, Jack Whitehall and Clare Balding film tennis comedy sketch for Unicef|url=http://blogs.unicef.org.uk/2015/06/16/andy-murray-liam-payne-one-drection-jack-whitehall-clare-balding-unicef-tennis-team-beat-disease/|publisher=Blogs.unicef.org.uk|accessdate=20 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222103034/http://blogs.unicef.org.uk/2015/06/16/andy-murray-liam-payne-one-drection-jack-whitehall-clare-balding-unicef-tennis-team-beat-disease/|archivedate=22 December 2015}}</ref> Payne teamed up with motorsport star [[Eddie Jordan]] in support of UK based charity [[CLIC Sargent]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee |first1=David |title=One Direction singer Liam Payne and sporting legends support CLIC Sargent event at Royal Windsor Racecourse |url=http://www.windsorexpress.co.uk/News/Areas/Windsor/Sporting-legends-and-One-Direction-singer-support-childrens-cancer-charity-event-at-Royal-Windsor-Racecourse-23062015.htm |work=Windsor Express |accessdate=20 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222102049/http://www.windsorexpress.co.uk/News/Areas/Windsor/Sporting-legends-and-One-Direction-singer-support-childrens-cancer-charity-event-at-Royal-Windsor-Racecourse-23062015.htm |archivedate=22 December 2015}}</ref> Payne is an ambassador for the charitable organization Trekstock.<ref>{{cite news|title=1D stars Liam Payne and Harry Styles become cancer charity ambassadors|url=http://www.itv.com/news/central/update/2015-04-20/1d-stars-liam-payne-and-harry-styles-become-cancer-charity-ambassadors/|publisher=Itv.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> Payne's original campaign with the organization in 2013 raised $784,198.<ref>{{cite news|title=An Evening Out With Liam and Harry|url=https://www.prizeo.com/prizes/liam-and-harry/an-evening-out-with-liam-and-harry|publisher=Prizeo.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> He raised an additional $211,237 during his campaign in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Charitable Nature of Liam Payne|url=http://trendom.co/the-charitable-nature-of-liam-payne/|publisher=Trendom.co|accessdate=20 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222083725/http://trendom.co/the-charitable-nature-of-liam-payne/|archive-date=22 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Payne has also been named an ambassador of [[Sustainable Development Goals]] also known as the Global Goals campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalgoals.org/ |title=The Global Goals |publisher=The Global Goals |date= |accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Global Goals Campaign Video|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6708119/one-direction-jennifer-lopez-global-goals-video|publisher=Billboard.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> Payne also gave a much needed push to a \u00a36 million youth project \"The Youth Zone\" in his hometown of Wolverhampton.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2015/04/28/one-direction-star-liam-payne-in-wolverhampton-for-youth-zone-event/|title=WATCH: Newly-released footage of One Direction star Liam Payne at Wolverhampton Youth Zone event|website=Expressandstar.com}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n=== Relationships ===\nIn 2016, Payne started dating [[Cheryl (singer)|Cheryl]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/cheryl-fernandez-versini-moves-in-with-liam-payne-116041000053_1.html|title=Cheryl Fernandez-Versini moves in with Liam Payne?|publisher=Business Standard|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414082834/http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/cheryl-fernandez-versini-moves-in-with-liam-payne-116041000053_1.html|archivedate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/753881/liam-payne-and-cheryl-fernandez-versini-are-madly-in-love-and-very-happy-according-to-simon-cowell|title=Liam Payne and Cheryl Fernandez-Versini are \"Madly in Love\" and \"Very Happy,\" According to Simon Cowell|publisher=E! Online|author=Vulpo, Mike|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008105055/http://www.eonline.com/news/753881/liam-payne-and-cheryl-fernandez-versini-are-madly-in-love-and-very-happy-according-to-simon-cowell|archivedate=8 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-44677975|title=Cheryl and Liam Payne announce split|date=1 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=1 July 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> they have one son (b.2017). They split in 2018.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite news|author1=Entertainment & Arts|title=Cheryl and Liam announce birth of baby boy|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-39395996|accessdate=25 March 2017|work=BBC News|date=25 March 2017|location=United Kingdom|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326060246/http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-39395996|archivedate=26 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Read-Dominguez|first1=Jennifer|title=Cheryl and Liam welcome their first child|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/news/a823511/cheryl-fernandez-versini-liam-payne-welcome-first-baby/|website=Digital Spy|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|accessdate=25 March 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325212737/http://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/news/a823511/cheryl-fernandez-versini-liam-payne-welcome-first-baby/|archivedate=25 March 2017|location=United Kingdom|language=en|date=25 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bacardi|first1=Francesca|title=Liam Payne and Cheryl Cole Welcome First Child Together|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/827620/liam-payne-and-cheryl-cole-welcome-their-first-child-together|website=[[E! Online]]|publisher=NBCUniversal|accessdate=9 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509140340/http://www.eonline.com/news/827620/liam-payne-and-cheryl-cole-welcome-their-first-child-together|archivedate=9 May 2017|location=United States|date=25 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2019, Payne confirmed that he was in a relationship with model Maya Henry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/liam-payne-makes-relationship-with-maya-henry-instagram-official/|title=Liam Payne Goes Instagram Official With Maya Henry 1 Year After Cheryl Split|date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Liam Payne discography}}\n* ''[[LP1 (Liam Payne album) |LP1]]'' (2019)\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[iCarly]]''\n| Himself\n|Guest role; Episode: \"[[ICarly (season 6)#Ep86|iGo One Direction]]\"\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[One Direction: This Is Us]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2014\n| ''[[One Direction: Where We Are - The Concert Film|Where We Are \u2013 The Concert Film]]''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dynamo: Magician Impossible]]''\n| Himself\n| Guest role; Season 4, episode 1\n|-\n|''[[Dancing with the Stars]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Watch One Direction's Liam Payne Learn Sadie Robertson's 'DWTS' Quack Attack Dance|url=https://www.yahoo.com/tv/bp/one-direction-liam-payne-sadie-robertson-dwts-video-151226726.html|publisher=Yahoo.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n| Himself\n| Guest role; Season 19, episode 13\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Himself\n| Voice role; Episode: \"[[Run, Chris, Run]]\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Drop the Mic]]''\n| Himself\n| Episode: \"[[Niecy Nash]] vs. [[Cedric the Entertainer]] / Liam Payne vs. [[Jason Derulo]]\"\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{See also|List of awards and nominations received by One Direction}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Organization\n! Category\n! Nominee/work\n! Result\n! {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]''\n|Sexiest Man of the Year\n| Liam Payne\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://attitude.co.uk/article/attitude-sexiest-man-of-the-year-award-liam-payne/8383/|title=Attitude Sexiest Man of the Year Award: Liam Payne|date=14 October 2015|website=Attitude.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[BMI Awards|BMI]] London Awards\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Pop Award Songs\n|\"Night Changes\"\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/2016-bmi-london-awards |title=Sting and Top Songwriters Honored at 2016 BMI London Awards |date=10 October 2016 |website=Bmi.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"Steal My Girl\"\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2017\n| rowspan=2| [[2017 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Summer Male Artist\n| rowspan=2| Liam Payne\n|{{won}}\n| rowspan=2|<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.teenchoice.com/so-you-think-you-can-dance/article/second-and-final-wave-of-%E2%80%9Cteen-choice-2017%E2%80%9D-nominees-announced |title=Second and Final Weave of \"Teen Choice 2017\" Nominees Announced |work=Teen Choice |date=13 July 2017 |accessdate=16 July 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice Male Hottie\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=15| 2018\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[2018 Brit Awards|Brit Awards]]\n| British Single\n| rowspan=\"2\"| \"Strip That Down\" {{small|(featuring Quavo)}}\n| {{no