{"title_page": "Cnemaspis dissanayakai", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| genus = Cnemaspis\n| species = dissanayakai\n| authority = Karunarathna, Silva, Bauer & Botejue, 2019\n}}\n\n'''''Cnemaspis dissanayakai''''', or '''Dissanayaka's day gecko''', is a species of diurnal [[gecko]] endemic to island of [[Sri Lanka]], described in 2019 from [[Polonnaruwa District|Polonnaruwa]].<ref name= kotagama>{{cite web |url=https://novataxa.blogspot.com/2020/01/cnemaspis-kotagamai.html|title=Cnemaspis kotagamai, C. dissanayakai & C. kawminiae \u2022 Three New Species of Day Geckos (Gekkonidae: Cnemaspis Strauch, 1887) from Isolated Granite Cave Habitats in Sri Lanka |publisher=Zootaxa |accessdate=2 January 2020|date=January 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe specific name ''dissanayakai'' is named in honor of Dissanayaka Mudiyanselage Karunarathna, who is the father of Suranjan Karunarathna, first author. His father supported the research team financially as well as encourage them including his son.<ref name= kotagama />\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe species is closely related to ''C. kumarasinghei '' and ''C. latha'' morphological aspects.<ref name= kotagama /><ref name= newsp>{{cite web|url=http://amphibian-reptile-conservation.org/pdfs/Volume/Vol_13_no_2/ARC_13_2_[General_Section]_323-354_e216.pdf|title=Three new species of day geckos (Reptilia: Gekkonidae: Cnemaspis Strauch, 1887) from isolated granite cave habitats in Sri Lanka |publisher=Journal of Amphibian & Reptile Conservation|accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nThe species was discovered from a tropical dry-mixed evergreen forest in [[Dimbulagala]], Polonnaruwa.<ref name= kotagama />\n\n==Description==\nSnout to vent length is 28.2&nbsp;mm in adult male and 29.4&nbsp;mm in adult female. Granular scales subconical. Chin, gular, pectoral, and abdominal scales are smooth. There are 105\u2013107 paravertebral granules. Two precloacal pore present. In males, 4\u20135 femoral pores present. Median row with an irregular diamond-shaped small scales series. Head small with long snout. Small eyes with round pupils. Dorsum of head, body and limbs generally dull brown. There are five \u2018W\u2019-shaped dark brown markings on the trunk. An oblique black line between eye and nostrils. Two straight dark brown postorbital stripes runs through eye to postero-ventrally. Tail dorsally grey pinkish with 5-7 faded black cross-bands.<ref name= newsp />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q85753068}}\n\n[[Category:Reptiles of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Cnemaspis|dissanayakai]]\n[[Category:Reptiles described in 2019]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| genus = Cnemaspis\n| species = dissanayakai\n| authority = Karunarathna, Silva, Bauer & Botejue, 2019\n}}\n\n'''''Cnemaspis dissanayakai''''', or '''Dissanayaka's day gecko''', is a species of diurnal [[gecko]] endemic to island of [[Sri Lanka]], described in 2019 from [[Polonnaruwa District|Polonnaruwa]].<ref name= kotagama>{{cite web |url=https://novataxa.blogspot.com/2020/01/cnemaspis-kotagamai.html|title=Cnemaspis kotagamai, C. dissanayakai & C. kawminiae \u2022 Three New Species of Day Geckos (Gekkonidae: Cnemaspis Strauch, 1887) from Isolated Granite Cave Habitats in Sri Lanka |publisher=Zootaxa |accessdate=2 January 2020|date=January 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe specific name ''dissanayakai'' is named in honor of Dissanayaka Mudiyanselage Karunarathna, who is the father of Suranjan Karunarathna, first author. His father supported the research team financially as well as encourage them including his son.<ref name= kotagama />\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe species is closely related to ''C. kumarasinghei '' and ''C. latha'' morphological aspects.<ref name= kotagama /><ref name= newsp>{{cite web|url=http://amphibian-reptile-conservation.org/pdfs/Volume/Vol_13_no_2/ARC_13_2_[General_Section]_323-354_e216.pdf|title=Three new species of day geckos (Reptilia: Gekkonidae: Cnemaspis Strauch, 1887) from isolated granite cave habitats in Sri Lanka |publisher=Journal of Amphibian & Reptile Conservation|accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nThe species was discovered from a tropical dry-mixed evergreen forest in [[Dimbulagala]], Polonnaruwa.<ref name= kotagama />\n\n==Description==\nSnout to vent length is 28.2&nbsp;mm in adult male and 29.4&nbsp;mm in adult female. Granular scales subconical. Chin, gular, pectoral, and abdominal scales are smooth. There are 105\u2013107 paravertebral granules. Two precloacal pore present. In males, 4\u20135 femoral pores present. Median row with an irregular diamond-shaped small scales series. Head small with long snout. Small eyes with round pupils. Dorsum of head, body and limbs generally dull brown. There are five \u2018W\u2019-shaped dark brown markings on the trunk. An oblique black line between eye and nostrils. Two straight dark brown postorbital stripes runs though eye to postero-ventrally. Tail dorsally grey pinkish with 5-7 faded black cross-bands.<ref name= newsp />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q85753068}}\n\n[[Category:Reptiles of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Cnemaspis|dissanayakai]]\n[[Category:Reptiles described in 2019]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDescription:Typo fixing, replaced: runs though  \u2192  runs through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cnemaspis_dissanayakai"}
{"title_page": "1997\u201398 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports season\n| title               = 1997\u201398 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup\n| league              = [[FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup]]\n| sport               = Basketball\n| logo                = \n| logo_size           = \n| caption             = \n| duration            = \n| attendance          = \n| season              = \n| season_champs       = \n| MVP                 = \n| MVP_link            = \n| top_scorer          = \n| top_scorer_link     = \n| playoffs            = \n| playoffs_link       = \n| playoffs_MVP        = \n| finals              = Finals\n| finals_link         = 1997\u201398 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup Finals\n| finals_champ        = {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Scaligera Basket Verona|Riello Mash Verona]]\n| finals_runner-up    = {{flagicon|FRY}} [[KK Crvena zvezda|Crvena zvezda]]\n| final_four_MVP      = \n| final_four_MVP_link = \n| seasonslist         = \n| seasonslistnames    = FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup\n| prevseason_link     = 1996\u201397 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup\n| prevseason_year     = 1996\u201397\n| nextseason_year     = 1998\u201399\n| nextseason_link     = 1998\u201399 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup\n}}\nThe '''1997\u201398 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup''' was the 26th edition of the third tier European basketball tournament [[FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup|FIBA Kora\u0107 cup]] and had 84 participants (42 teams played from the first round and another 42 teams from the second round). [[Riello Mash Verona]] won the tournament.\n\n== Team allocation ==\nThe labels in the parentheses show how each team qualified for the place of its starting round:\n\n* 1st, 2nd, 3rd, etc.: League position after Playoffs\n* WC: [[Wild card (sports)|Wild card]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"white-space: nowrap;\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 | [[#First qualifying round|First round]]\n|-\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Mons-Hainaut|Belgacom Union Mons]] (3rd)\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|POR}} [[S.C. Beira-Mar|Aveiro]]\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|FRY}} [[KK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]] ([[YUBA League|5th]]) {{Cref2|Note VOJ}}\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|SWE}} [[S\u00f6dert\u00e4lje BBK|Astra S\u00f6dert\u00e4lje]] ([[Basketligan|5th]])\n|-\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Echo Houthalen]]\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|POR}} [[S.L. Benfica (basketball)|Benfica]]\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|FRY}} [[KK Spartak Subotica|Spartak Subotica]] ([[YUBA League|6th]])\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Namika Lahti|Lahti Logistics]] ([[Korisliiga|7th]])\n|-\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|LUX}} [[BBC R\u00e9sidence|R\u00e9sidense]] ([[Total League|1st]])\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|POR}} [[C.A. Queluz|Queluz]]\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|FRY}} [[KK Crvena zvezda|Crvena Zvezda]] ([[YUBA League|12th]])\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|FIN}} [[UU-Korihait|Saab Uusikaupunki]] ([[Korisliiga|8th]])\n|-\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|LUX}} [[BBC Sparta Bertrange|Sparta Bertrange]] ([[Total League|2nd]])\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|ROM}} [[CS Dinamo Bucure\u0219ti (basketball)|Dinamo Bucure\u015fti]] ([[Liga Na\u021bional\u0103 (men's basketball)|1st]])\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|CRO}} [[KK Dubrava|Benston Zagreb]] ([[HT Premijer liga|3rd]])\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|EST}} [[TT\u00dc-A. Le Coq|Estonian Fairs]] ([[Korvpalli Meistriliiga|1st]])\n|-\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|AUT}} [[Oberwart Gunners|Stahlbau Oberwart]] ([[\u00d6sterreichische Basketball Bundesliga|2nd]])\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|ROM}} [[CSA Steaua Bucure\u0219ti (basketball)|Steaua Bucure\u015fti]] ([[Liga Na\u021bional\u0103 (men's basketball)|2nd]])\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|BIH}} [[HKK Brotnjo|Brotnjo]]\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|LAT}} [[BK Ventspils|Ventspils]] ([[Latvijas Basketbola l\u012bga|4th]])\n|-\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|AUT}} [[Kapfenberg Bulls|Montan Kapfenberg]] ([[\u00d6sterreichische Basketball Bundesliga|3rd]])\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|BUL}} [[Slavia Sofia (sports club)|Slavia Sofia]] ([[National Basketball League (Bulgaria)|1st]])\n| width=210 | {{flagicon|BIH}} [[KK \u010ce\u0161ko|\u010ce\u0161ko]